const CITY_SIDING_EXTRA = {
  "new-york-ny": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `NYC framed-housing siding on Staten Island single-family and Queens detached housing is dominated by vinyl at .046" gauge or thicker. Fiber cement (James Hardie HardiePlank and HardieShingle) appears on higher-end Brooklyn and Queens renovations and some Staten Island new construction. Masonry-brick and brownstone elevations across Park Slope, Bay Ridge, Astoria, and Harlem dominate pre-war housing stock and require tuckpointing rather than siding replacement. Pre-war wood clapboard survives on some Victorian-era housing in Victorian Flatbush, Douglaston Hill, and Cambria Heights.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `NYC has 37,000+ LPC-designated properties across 150+ historic districts including Greenwich Village, SoHo-Cast Iron, Brooklyn Heights, Park Slope, DUMBO, Tribeca West, Ladies' Mile, Upper East Side, Upper West Side/Central Park West, Stonewall, Weeksville, and Victorian Flatbush. LPC Rules §63-8 governs facade replacement on landmarked properties. Approved siding materials vary by district but typically include period-appropriate wood clapboard, brick repointing, brownstone restoration, or pressed-metal restoration on commercial-era facades. Vinyl and most modern composite products are categorically prohibited on contributing structures.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `NYC DOB NOW permit filing for straight facade replacement runs 5-10 business days via registered HIC. Scope changes including window-size modification, siding-to-masonry transition work, or facade insulation upgrades trigger Plan Examiner review adding 4-10 weeks. Landmarked LPC Certificate of No Effect runs 6-10 weeks; CofA runs 12-24 weeks. Multi-family buildings additionally require DOB Tenant Protection Plans. Scaffold permits through DOB Scaffold Unit run $2,500-$12,000 depending on duration and street exposure.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `NYC coastal zones (Rockaway Peninsula, Staten Island South Shore, Breezy Point, Coney Island, City Island) see significant salt-air corrosion on fasteners and aluminum trim components. Stainless steel 304 or 316 fasteners are the durable NYC coastal spec; galvanized steel pits and stains within 3-5 years in salt-spray environments. FEMA V-zone and coastal A-zone mapping from post-Sandy updates affects elevation and sheathing choices on NYC coastal reconstruction. Flood-resistant materials per FEMA Technical Bulletin 2 apply below design flood elevation.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `NYC paint-compatibility considerations: vinyl siding manufacturer warranties commonly void on painted installations; HardieColor Plus and HardiePlank ColorPlus technology pre-painted products carry 15-year fade warranty. Field-painted fiber cement requires 100% acrylic exterior-grade primer and topcoat with manufacturer-approved paint systems (Sherwin-Williams Duration, Benjamin Moore Regal Select, Behr Marquee). Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (most NYC brownstones and rowhouses) trigger EPA RRP scope requiring certified firm and specific work practices.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `NYC insulation integration with siding replacement is increasingly common under NYSERDA Home Performance with ENERGY STAR program. Continuous exterior insulation (R-5 to R-10 rigid foam or mineral wool) outboard of sheathing plus siding reduces thermal bridging through stud cavities. NYC Energy Conservation Construction Code (2020) requires specific wall assembly performance on major renovations; siding replacement without insulation upgrade may fail energy inspection on ENERGY STAR-certified retrofit scope. Vapor-open assemblies with exterior-side mineral wool perform well in NYC climate.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `NYC pressure-wash prep before siding installation is critical on pre-1978 homes due to lead-paint considerations: EPA RRP rules require specific containment and HEPA-vacuum cleanup; high-pressure water washing of lead-painted substrates is prohibited except with specific containment protocols. Legitimate NYC siding installers pressure-wash clean existing substrate at 1,500-2,500 PSI with detergent for biological growth removal, with appropriate lead-safe containment where required. Mold and mildew abatement prior to installation is cheap insurance against future substrate failure.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `NYC siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers NYC metro from the Cherry Hill NJ office with direct support on Master Elite-equivalent installer certification. CertainTeed operates from Malvern PA with NYC metro rep coverage. Mastic (Ply Gem) handles vinyl siding. LP SmartSide engineered wood ships through Atlantic region distribution. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple metro locations), Beacon Building Products, Patrick Industries, and SRS Distribution, each with same-day or next-day stock pickup.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `NYC siding installer tiering: small owner-operator crews (3-6 man teams) dominate Queens and Staten Island residential with $45-$75 per linear foot labor rates on vinyl. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $85-$140 per linear foot on fiber cement. Union-shop premium crews with specialty historic-restoration expertise run $150-$300 per linear foot on landmarked Brooklyn and Upper East Side projects. NYC labor premium over national average runs 1.8-2.3x for most work, 2.5-3.2x for landmarked-district specialty work.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `NYC siding upsells worth accepting: continuous exterior insulation (thermal bridging reduction + NYSERDA rebate eligibility), stainless-steel fasteners on coastal-adjacent properties (prevents 3-5 year fastener failure), HardiePlank ColorPlus or similar factory-finished product (15-year fade warranty vs field-paint uncertainty), and pre-installation lead-safe substrate preparation on pre-1978 homes. Upsells to decline: "rowhouse-specialist" proprietary products without independent ASTM certification, unnecessary decorative-trim additions beyond existing facade profile, and "hurricane-guaranteed" vinyl claims lacking documented wind-load ratings.`,
    marketSizePara: `NYC has approximately 180,000 single-family pitched-roof homes across Staten Island, Queens, and parts of Brooklyn and the Bronx with framed siding exposure. Staten Island alone contains 120,000+ framed single-family homes with replaceable siding scope. Pre-war brick and brownstone housing (Brooklyn, Manhattan, Bronx) totals another 280,000+ but requires tuckpointing rather than siding replacement. NYC DOB pulls approximately 8,000-14,000 siding permits annually across all replacement scope. Staten Island dominates volume at roughly 45-55% of NYC-wide siding permit count.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `NYC siding pricing peaks April through September during optimal install conditions and real-estate closing season. November through February sub-freezing ambient temperatures compromise vinyl impact resistance and caulk activation; most NYC contractors stop vinyl work when temperatures drop below 32F. Fiber cement can install in cold weather with proper primer selection but labor premiums run 15-25% from December through February. Best pricing typically runs October-November (10-18% below peak) and late March (before April surge). Landmarked LPC review cycles often dictate scheduling more than weather.`,
  },
  "los-angeles-ca": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `LA's dominant siding material is 3-coat stucco (scratch, brown, finish) over paper-and-lath on Spanish Colonial, Mediterranean, ranch, and Monterey-style homes. Fiber cement (James Hardie HardiePlank) appears on higher-end Modernist and Craftsman rebuilds in Silver Lake, Los Feliz, and Highland Park. Wood siding (cedar, redwood) on Hollywood Hills and Brentwood architect-designed custom builds. Vinyl is rare; HOA restrictions in Pacific Palisades, Brentwood, Hancock Park, and most HPOZ districts prohibit it. Cedar shingle and shake appear on some 1920s craftsman bungalow restorations.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `LA has 35+ Historic Preservation Overlay Zones (HPOZ) including Angelino Heights, Carthay Circle, Country Club Park, Gregory Ain Mar Vista Tract, Harvard Heights, Highland Park-Garvanza, Hollywood Grove, Jefferson Park, Lincoln Heights, Melrose Hill, Miracle Mile North, South Carthay, Spaulding Square, Van Nuys, West Adams Terrace, Westwood Square, Whitley Heights, and Wilshire Park. HPOZ review requires matching original siding material and profile on contributing structures. Stucco restoration requires specific texture and color matching to Merrick-era or period-appropriate originals.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `LADBS permits residential siding replacement over-the-counter for about $250 plus $45 plan-check fee on same-day review. Scope changes trigger plan-check review at 2-6 weeks. HPOZ properties require Cultural Heritage Commission notice before permit issuance adding 4-8 weeks. CalRecycle 65% debris-diversion mandate applies to siding tear-off; documented receipts from certified recycling facilities required at final inspection. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP scope plus California-specific CDPH lead-safe certification.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `LA coastal zones within 3-5 miles of the beach (Venice, Mar Vista, Santa Monica, Pacific Palisades, Malibu) see significant salt-air corrosion on fasteners and aluminum trim components. Stainless steel 304 or 316 fasteners are the durable LA coastal spec; galvanized steel pits within 3-5 years. Marine-coated aluminum or copper are coastal-durable trim materials. California Coastal Commission jurisdiction adds permit complexity on Coastal Zone properties (approximately 1 mile inland from high-tide line). Stucco in marine environments requires specific waterproofing and drainage-plane detail.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `LA paint-compatibility considerations: stucco color refresh typically runs 10-15 year cycles on south and west elevations due to UV fade; north and east typically 20+ years. Dark-colored stucco fades visibly within 8-12 years in LA UV. Elastomeric coatings (Dunn-Edwards, Frazee, Sherwin-Williams) provide crack-bridging and UV resistance at 15-20 year service. Fiber cement painting uses 100% acrylic exterior products. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP scope; most LA post-war tract construction is post-1978 and lead-free.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `LA insulation integration with siding replacement is common under LADWP Consumer Rebate Program envelope credits. Continuous exterior insulation (R-5 to R-8 rigid foam or mineral wool) outboard of sheathing plus siding reduces thermal bridging in cooling-dominated LA climate. Title 24 Part 6 (2022) requires specific wall assembly performance on major renovations. Spray foam on wood-framed siding substrates provides moisture resistance plus thermal improvement. Stucco re-coat projects rarely include insulation upgrade due to stucco's inherent thermal mass and existing wall assembly.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `LA pressure-wash prep before siding installation: stucco repair requires moisture testing first, scope documentation, and proper 3-coat application over new paper-and-lath in damaged areas. Fiber cement and wood siding substrates pressure-wash clean at 1,500-2,500 PSI with detergent for biological growth removal prior to installation. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (rare in LA post-war tract construction, common in HPOZ landmarked homes) trigger EPA RRP scope requiring certified firm. Stucco moisture testing using moisture meter identifies hidden sheathing rot before new finish.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `LA siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers LA from the Fontana CA distribution center with direct installer certification support. CertainTeed operates from California plants with regional rep coverage. Dryvit (EIFS systems) serves LA stucco specialty market. LP SmartSide ships through regional distribution. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple LA County locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Anderson Truss supply with same-day or next-day stock pickup. La Habra Stucco (La Habra CA) is regional stucco manufacturer serving LA market.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `LA siding installer tiering: stucco specialty crews (C-35 plastering and lathing license) dominate residential market at $8-$14 per square foot on 3-coat stucco installation. Fiber cement crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $10-$18 per square foot. Premium specialty crews with HPOZ historic-restoration expertise run $18-$35 per square foot on landmarked Angelino Heights and West Adams projects. LA labor premium over national average runs 1.3-1.7x for standard work, 2-2.8x for HPOZ specialty work. Crews with current CSLB license and active workers' compensation coverage are the verifiable baseline.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `LA siding upsells worth accepting: drainage-plane installation with weather-resistive barrier behind stucco (critical in marine-adjacent zones), stainless-steel fasteners on coastal-adjacent properties, HardieColor Plus or similar factory-finished product on fiber cement (15-year fade warranty), and Class A fire-rated assembly in WUI zones (mandatory for FAIR Plan eligibility). Upsells to decline: elastomeric coating as substitute for proper stucco repair (hides moisture damage without fixing it), unnecessary decorative additions beyond existing facade profile, and "coastal-specific" proprietary products lacking California Coastal Commission-approved documentation.`,
    marketSizePara: `LA County has approximately 1.9 million single-family homes, with roughly 70% stucco, 15% fiber cement or wood (concentrated in higher-end and historic neighborhoods), 8% other (brick veneer, stone, specialty), and 7% vinyl or aluminum (older tract construction). LADBS plus LA County unincorporated pulls approximately 25,000-40,000 siding permits annually across all replacement scope. Stucco repair and recoat projects are often permitted as maintenance rather than replacement, so permit data understates actual volume. HPOZ landmarked siding scope represents 3-5% of annual total.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `LA siding pricing peaks October through April outside peak fire season and summer-surface-heat extremes. May through September WUI fire-season access restrictions affect hillside scheduling during Red Flag Warning days. Summer surface temperatures above 110F disrupt stucco cure and make fiber cement installation uncomfortable. Winter (December-February) atmospheric-river rainfall occasionally disrupts stucco cure but fiber cement and wood siding can install year-round. Best pricing typically runs January-March (5-12% below peak). California Coastal Commission permit cycles dictate timing on coastal-zone properties more than weather.`,
  },
  "chicago-il": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Chicago's dominant siding material is brick masonry on greystone and brick bungalow housing throughout the Bungalow Belt (Portage Park, Norwood Park, Jefferson Park, Mayfair), which dominates Chicago residential at 40-50%. Vinyl at .046" gauge or thicker appears on framed bungalow rear additions, two-flat and three-flat exposed elevations, and Ravenswood and Lakeview wood-framed single-family. Fiber cement (James Hardie HardiePlank) on higher-end renovations in Lincoln Park, Wicker Park, Andersonville, and Bucktown. Wood clapboard on landmarked Old Town and Pullman historic homes.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Chicago has 60+ designated historic districts under Commission on Chicago Landmarks jurisdiction including Old Town Triangle, Pullman, Prairie Avenue, Astor Street, Kenwood, Hyde Park-Kenwood, East Village, West Loop Industrial Historic District, and Alta Vista Terrace. Landmarked facade replacement requires matching original siding material and profile. Chicago Landmark Ordinance Chapter 2-120 governs review. Approved materials typically include period-appropriate wood clapboard, brick repointing, or specific stone restoration matching 1880s-1920s construction. Modern vinyl and most composite products prohibited on contributing structures.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `Chicago DOB E-Permit for straight facade replacement runs 24-72 hours via registered Chicago GC. Scope changes trigger Plan Examination at 2-6 weeks. Landmarked Commission on Chicago Landmarks Permit Review adds 4-10 weeks. Dumpster placement permits through Chicago DOT run $60 per day plus tree-protection and alley-access fees. Asbestos in pre-1980 exterior cladding requires Illinois EPA notification and licensed abatement, adding $2,000-$6,500. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (majority of Chicago housing stock) trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Chicago has no coastal saltwater exposure but Lake Michigan shoreline properties (Rogers Park, Edgewater, Hyde Park, South Shore) experience freeze-thaw moisture cycling on lakefront elevations. Chicago DOT winter road-salt spray across lakefront neighborhoods corrodes fasteners and aluminum trim within 3-5 years on uncoated galvanized steel. Stainless-steel 304 or 316 fasteners are the durable lake-effect spec. Harbor and marina-adjacent properties see additional corrosion exposure. Lake-effect snow-load on framed siding at roof-wall transitions drives structural-reinforcement requirements on some tear-off renovations.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Chicago paint-compatibility considerations: Chicago freeze-thaw cycling is particularly hard on paint film adhesion; 10-year re-paint cycles are standard on wood clapboard, 15-20 years on fiber cement with factory finish. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (most Chicago housing) trigger EPA RRP scope. Oil-based primers outperform acrylic primers on aged wood clapboard in Chicago climate. Chicago freeze-thaw also stresses caulk and sealant; 35-year silicone sealants at all penetrations are the durable Chicago spec rather than acrylic-latex alternatives.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Chicago insulation integration with siding replacement is incentivized under ComEd Energy Efficiency Program plus Peoples Gas rebates plus Illinois Home Weatherization Assistance Program. Continuous exterior insulation (R-8 to R-15 rigid foam or mineral wool) outboard of sheathing plus siding dramatically reduces thermal bridging in cold-climate Chicago. Chicago Energy Conservation Code §18-13-101 requires specific wall assembly performance on major renovations. Blower-door testing verifies air-tightness on conservation-improvement-funded jobs. R-20+ total wall assembly performance meets Chicago Stretch Code on retrofit scope.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Chicago pressure-wash prep before siding installation: freeze-thaw-damaged substrates require moisture testing and repair before new siding installation. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (nearly all Chicago Bungalow Belt) trigger EPA RRP scope requiring certified firm and specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup. High-pressure water washing of lead-painted substrates is prohibited except with containment. Legitimate Chicago installers pressure-wash at 1,500-2,500 PSI with detergent for biological growth removal, with lead-safe containment where required.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Chicago siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Chicago metro from Midwest regional office. CertainTeed operates from Shakopee MN and Avery OH plants with Chicago rep coverage. Mastic (Ply Gem) handles vinyl siding. LP SmartSide ships from Midwest plants. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple Chicago metro locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products with same-day or next-day pickup. Feldco (Des Plaines IL) is a major Chicago-area siding installer with its own supply network. Chicago Millwork supplies specialty landmark-restoration components.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Chicago siding installer tiering: small owner-operator vinyl-specialty crews dominate Bungalow Belt and working-class neighborhoods at $8-$14 per square foot installed. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $12-$22 per square foot on fiber cement. Landmark-restoration crews with Commission on Chicago Landmarks expertise run $22-$45 per square foot on Old Town, Pullman, and Prairie Avenue projects. Chicago labor premium over national average runs 1.2-1.5x for standard work, 1.8-2.3x for landmarked specialty work. Active Chicago GC license plus bond status is the verifiable baseline.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Chicago siding upsells worth accepting: continuous exterior insulation (R-8+ rigid foam or mineral wool, ComEd rebate eligibility), .046"+ gauge vinyl (avoids cold-weather impact failure), fiber cement factory-finished ColorPlus or similar (15-year fade warranty), and lead-safe substrate preparation on pre-1978 homes. Upsells to decline: "Chicago-tough" proprietary vinyl products without documented cold-weather impact testing, unnecessary decorative additions beyond existing facade profile, and builder-grade .040" thin-gauge vinyl that cracks in sub-zero ambient. Thin-gauge vinyl installed at $6-$10 per square foot is false economy.`,
    marketSizePara: `Chicago city has approximately 565,000 residential structures; the Bungalow Belt alone contains 80,000+ brick bungalows with framed rear-addition siding scope. Two-flat and three-flat housing dominates North and Northwest Sides with 125,000+ multi-family units with framed-siding elevations. Chicago metro (Cook, DuPage, Will, Kane, Lake, McHenry counties) totals approximately 2.6 million residential units. Chicago DOB pulls approximately 12,000-20,000 siding permits annually city-wide; metro-wide runs 55,000-85,000. Commission on Chicago Landmarks work represents 2-4% of annual city-wide volume.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Chicago siding pricing peaks May through October during optimal install conditions between sub-freezing winter and summer humidity extremes. November through April sub-freezing ambient temperatures compromise vinyl impact resistance and caulk activation; most Chicago contractors stop vinyl work when temperatures drop below 32F. Fiber cement can install in cold weather with proper primer but labor premiums run 15-30% from December through February. Best pricing typically runs late September-October and early May (10-18% below peak). Landmark Commission review on Old Town and Pullman often dictates scheduling more than weather.`,
  },
  "houston-tx": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Houston's dominant siding material is brick veneer on 1970s-2010s tract construction across Harris County, which dominates at 60-70% of residential. Hardie fiber cement on higher-end replacements in The Heights, Memorial, West University, and Montrose. Vinyl on older ranch and cottage homes across outer Harris County and Fort Bend County. Brick veneer typically outlasts the home's framing, so siding replacement projects in Houston involve fiber cement, wood, or vinyl on framed gables, dormers, second-story sections rather than full-home material swaps. Wood clapboard on landmarked Heights bungalows.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Houston has 22+ historic districts under Archaeological and Historical Commission (HAHC) jurisdiction including Heights (East/West/South), Old Sixth Ward, Broadacres, Audubon Place, Main Street Market Square, Avondale, Courtlandt Place, First Montrose Commons, Freeland, Glenbrook Valley, MacGregor Way, Norhill, Old Braeswood, Riverside Terrace, Westmoreland Place, and Woodland Heights. HAHC review applies to contributing structures. Approved siding materials typically include period-appropriate wood clapboard matching original profile on bungalow-era homes, brick restoration, or specific fiber cement profiles matching the original pattern. Vinyl prohibited on most contributing structures.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `City of Houston Building Department permits siding replacement over 100 square feet through the online portal within 48-72 hours for straightforward replacements. Harris County unincorporated uses the Harris County Permit Office with similar timelines. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-5 weeks. HAHC historic review adds 4-8 weeks on contributing structures. Dumpster placement is straightforward on typical Houston lots with adequate driveway space. Asbestos in pre-1980 cladding requires TCEQ notification and licensed abatement. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Houston coastal-adjacent zones (Clear Lake, Kemah, Seabrook, La Porte, Baytown, and Galveston Bay-facing properties) experience significant salt-air corrosion on fasteners and aluminum trim. Stainless steel 304 or 316 fasteners are the durable Houston coastal spec; galvanized steel pits within 3-5 years in Gulf-coast environments. TWIA (Texas Windstorm Insurance Association) coastal-zone coverage in Galveston County requires WPI-8 certification on siding installations. Hurricane wind-uplift on siding requires ASTM D3161 Class F or D7158 Class H ratings as baseline spec.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Houston paint-compatibility considerations: 95%+ humidity year-round is particularly hard on paint film adhesion; 7-12 year re-paint cycles are standard on wood clapboard, 15-year factory-finish fiber cement ColorPlus is meaningfully longer. Oil-based primers outperform acrylic primers on aged wood substrates in Houston humidity. Mildew-resistant paint additives are essential; Benjamin Moore MoorGlo, Sherwin-Williams SuperPaint with mildew resistance, and Behr Premium Plus Ultra are Houston-proven. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (concentrated in Heights and pre-WWII housing) trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Houston insulation integration with siding replacement is less common than cold-climate markets due to cooling-dominated load and slab-on-grade construction. CenterPoint Energy offers envelope credits on ENERGY STAR-qualifying insulated siding retrofits. Continuous exterior insulation (R-5 to R-8 rigid foam) outboard of sheathing plus siding reduces thermal bridging. Radiant barrier on wall assembly reduces solar gain on west-facing elevations in cooling-dominated Houston. Vapor-open assemblies with exterior-side rigid foam perform well; vapor-closed assemblies can trap moisture in Gulf humidity.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Houston pressure-wash prep before siding installation: heavy humidity-driven biological growth (mildew, algae, mold) requires aggressive cleaning before new siding installation. 2,500-3,500 PSI pressure wash with bleach-based detergent (3-5% sodium hypochlorite solution) is Houston standard. Termite inspection of wood fascia and sheathing before installation is prudent; termite-damaged structural wood must be replaced before new siding hides the damage. Post-Harvey flood-damaged homes require specific mold remediation and drying protocols (dew point below 50F for 3-5 days) before siding installation.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Houston siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Houston metro from Texas regional office; Hardie HQ is in Chicago but Texas market is well-supported. CertainTeed operates from Shreveport LA plant with Houston rep coverage. LP SmartSide ships from Texas plants. Mastic (Ply Gem) handles vinyl siding. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple Houston locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products with same-day or next-day pickup. La Habra Stucco serves Houston stucco specialty market. Wolfe Siding Products is regional installer supply network.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Houston siding installer tiering: small owner-operator vinyl-specialty crews dominate older tract replacement at $6-$11 per square foot installed. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $9-$16 per square foot on fiber cement. Landmark-restoration crews with HAHC expertise run $18-$35 per square foot on Heights bungalow and Old Sixth Ward projects. Houston labor premium over national average runs 1.0-1.3x due to low cost of living; premium specialty work is competitively priced compared to coastal metros. Active Texas Secretary of State business filing plus insurance certificates are verifiable baseline.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Houston siding upsells worth accepting: drainage-plane weather-resistive barrier behind brick veneer or fiber cement (critical in Gulf humidity), stainless-steel fasteners on coastal-adjacent properties, HardieColor Plus factory finish (15-year fade warranty), radiant-barrier integration on west-facing elevations. Upsells to decline: "hurricane-proof" vinyl products without ASTM wind-load documentation, unnecessary decorative additions beyond existing facade profile, cedar shingle in Houston humidity (delaminates within 3-5 years), and "termite-proof" proprietary treatments lacking independent efficacy documentation. Never assign insurance proceeds directly to a contractor.`,
    marketSizePara: `Harris County has approximately 1.2 million single-family homes, with roughly 65% brick veneer, 15% fiber cement on framed elevations, 12% vinyl, and 8% other (stucco, wood, stone veneer, EIFS). Houston-metro (Harris, Fort Bend, Montgomery, Brazoria, Galveston, Liberty, Waller, Chambers counties) totals approximately 2.1 million residential units. City of Houston plus Harris County pulls approximately 18,000-30,000 siding permits annually across all replacement scope. Post-Harvey 2017 and post-Beryl 2024 recovery added significant volume.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Houston siding pricing peaks October through February outside hurricane season and peak-humidity extremes. June through September hurricane season and 95%+ humidity disrupt install productivity; most Houston contractors stop work during hurricane warnings. Post-hurricane surge pricing after major events can double normal rates for 6-12 months. March through May spring-storm season drives claim-repair surge. Best pricing and scheduling typically runs October-November (10-18% below peak) and May (before hurricane season). HAHC review on Heights and Old Sixth Ward often dictates scheduling more than weather.`,
  },
  "phoenix-az": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Phoenix's dominant siding material is 3-coat stucco on block-wall and framed construction across the metro, which dominates at 75-85% of residential. Fiber cement (James Hardie HardiePlank) appears on higher-end Arcadia and Biltmore renovations and some new-construction tract homes. Vinyl and wood siding are rare due to extreme UV degradation; Phoenix UV chalks unprotected paint within 4-5 years and degrades vinyl within 8-12 years. 3-coat stucco (scratch, brown, finish) over paper-and-lath typically requires re-coat every 12-18 years to maintain color and crack resistance.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Phoenix has 40+ historic districts under Historic Preservation Office (HPO) jurisdiction including Willo, Encanto-Palmcroft, Coronado, Roosevelt, F.Q. Story, Del Norte Place, Ashland Place, Alvarado, Cheery Lynn, Country Club Park, Fairview Place, Garfield, La Hacienda, Lynwood, Midtown, North Encanto, Oakland, Phoenix Homesteads, Pierson Place, Pine Grove, Windsor Square, Woodlea, and Yaple Park. HPO review applies to contributing structures. Approved siding materials typically include period-appropriate stucco matching original texture, or specific fiber cement profiles on 1920s-1950s bungalow-era homes.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `Phoenix Development Services Department permits siding replacement through the SHAPE PHX online portal within 24-72 hours for straightforward replacements at $47 base fee. Maricopa County unincorporated uses the county permit office at $65-$120 per project. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-4 weeks. HPO historic review adds 4-8 weeks on contributing structures. HOA architectural approval in Ahwatukee, Desert Ridge, and Arcadia is often more time-consuming than city permit. Dumpster placement in HOA-controlled communities requires specific ARC pre-approval. Block-wall adhesion testing before stucco recoat.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Phoenix has no coastal saltwater exposure but monsoon-season dust-storm debris and Mojave blowing dust abrade stucco finish and deposit fine particulate on all surfaces. Dust-storm debris removal from wall surfaces annually prevents accelerated paint-film degradation. Fastener corrosion in Phoenix desert climate is minimal compared to coastal metros; galvanized steel fasteners perform adequately. UV degradation is the dominant Phoenix durability factor: unprotected paint chalks within 4-5 years, vinyl degrades within 8-12 years, dark-colored stucco fades within 8-12 years.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Phoenix paint-compatibility considerations: stucco color refresh typically runs 12-18 year cycles with re-coat rather than paint-over. Elastomeric coatings (Dunn-Edwards Enduracoat, Frazee Envirokote, Sherwin-Williams Duration) provide crack-bridging and UV resistance at 15-20 year service. Dark colors fade measurably within 8-12 years on south and west elevations due to Phoenix UV index averaging 10+ for six months annually. Fluoropolymer finishes (Kynar, Fluoropon) on fiber cement hold color 12-15 years and justify the 25% premium. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Phoenix insulation integration with siding replacement is common on framed (non-block-wall) construction under APS Home Performance with ENERGY STAR plus SRP Home Energy Checkup program rebates. Continuous exterior insulation (R-5 to R-8 rigid foam) outboard of sheathing plus stucco or fiber cement reduces thermal bridging in cooling-dominated Phoenix climate. Block-wall construction inherently provides thermal mass; insulation retrofits on block-wall walls typically use interior furring and batt rather than exterior rigid foam. Radiant barrier on wall assembly reduces solar gain on west-facing elevations.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Phoenix pressure-wash prep before siding installation: stucco repair requires moisture testing first using moisture meter to identify hidden substrate damage. Scope documentation and proper 3-coat application over new paper-and-lath in damaged areas is the legitimate protocol. Dust-storm particulate buildup on wall surfaces requires aggressive cleaning before new paint or finish application. 2,500-3,500 PSI pressure wash with detergent for dust removal. Block-wall adhesion testing before stucco recoat uses bond-quality patches tested after 48-hour cure to verify adequate adhesion.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Phoenix siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Phoenix from California regional office with direct installer certification support. CertainTeed operates from California plants with Phoenix rep coverage. LP SmartSide ships from regional distribution. La Habra Stucco (La Habra CA) is the dominant regional stucco manufacturer. Kelley Manufacturing is Phoenix-based stucco supply. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple Phoenix locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products with same-day pickup. Arizona ROC licensing (C-35 or B-General) is mandatory and publicly searchable.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Phoenix siding installer tiering: small owner-operator stucco-specialty crews (C-35 plastering license) dominate residential repair and recoat market at $4-$8 per square foot on single-coat elastomeric or $8-$14 per square foot on 3-coat. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $9-$16 per square foot on fiber cement. Landmark-restoration crews with HPO expertise run $15-$28 per square foot on Willo, Encanto-Palmcroft, and Coronado landmarked projects. Phoenix labor premium over national average runs 0.9-1.2x due to favorable cost of living.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Phoenix siding upsells worth accepting: elastomeric crack-bridging coating on recoat (prevents monsoon moisture intrusion through micro-cracks), UV-stabilized fluoropolymer finish on fiber cement (Kynar/Fluoropon, 12-15 year color warranty), stainless-steel fasteners on monsoon-exposed elevations, and Title 24-style reflective exterior surfaces on west-facing elevations. Upsells to decline: "desert-specific" proprietary products without documented UV testing, unnecessary decorative additions beyond existing facade profile, quickie elastomeric patches over cracked stucco without moisture testing or repair of underlying damage.`,
    marketSizePara: `Maricopa County has approximately 1.6 million single-family homes. Stucco dominates at roughly 78%, fiber cement at 10%, vinyl at 5%, and other (brick veneer, stone veneer, EIFS, wood) at 7%. Phoenix metro (Maricopa plus Pinal County) totals approximately 1.8 million residential units. Phoenix plus Maricopa County pulls approximately 15,000-28,000 siding permits annually across all replacement scope. HPO landmarked siding scope represents 2-3% of annual total. Stucco recoat projects are often permitted as maintenance rather than replacement.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Phoenix siding pricing peaks October through April outside monsoon season and 150F+ surface-temperature extremes. May through September surface temperatures restrict stucco cure and fiber cement installation to early-morning hours and extend project duration. Monsoon-season rain events from July through September further disrupt install windows. Best pricing is typically June-September (15-25% below peak) with the caveat that active-install scheduling is difficult. November through February is the optimal combination of pricing and install conditions. HOA ARC review cycles in master-planned communities often dictate scheduling more than weather.`,
  },
  "dallas-tx": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Dallas's dominant siding material is brick veneer on 1950s-2010s tract construction across Dallas County and surrounding counties, which dominates at 55-65% of residential. Hardie fiber cement on higher-end replacements in Highland Park, University Park, Preston Hollow, and Lakewood. Vinyl on older ranch homes across outer Dallas County and Tarrant County. Brick veneer typically outlasts the home's framing; replacement projects involve fiber cement or wood on framed gables, dormers, and second-story sections rather than full-home material swaps. Wood clapboard on landmarked Munger Place and Swiss Avenue bungalows.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Dallas has 20+ historic districts under Historic Preservation Office (HPO) jurisdiction including Munger Place, Swiss Avenue, State-Thomas, South Boulevard-Park Row, Winnetka Heights, Peak's Suburban Addition, Hardwick Street, Lake Cliff, Lakewood, Junius Heights, Wilshire Heights, Tenth Street, Kessler Park, Stevens Park, Monticello, Forest Avenue, Hammer Street, and Edgemont Park. HPO review applies to contributing structures. Approved siding materials typically include period-appropriate wood clapboard, brick restoration, or specific fiber cement profiles matching 1900s-1940s construction. Vinyl prohibited on most contributing structures.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `City of Dallas Residential Building Permit issues within 48-72 hours for like-for-like siding replacement under residential fast-track at $92 minimum. Suburban cities (Plano, Richardson, Irving, Arlington, Fort Worth, Frisco) use separate permit processes. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-5 weeks. HPO historic review adds 4-8 weeks on contributing structures. Asbestos in pre-1980 exterior cladding requires TCEQ notification and licensed abatement. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP scope; most Dallas post-war tract construction is post-1978 and lead-free.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Dallas has no coastal saltwater exposure; corrosion concerns center on Houston Black clay soil movement that stresses framing and siding seams over 15-25 year cycles. Foundation movement on East Dallas and Oak Cliff homes built on expansive clay causes siding-to-sheathing attachment stress. Hail impact on fasteners and aluminum trim is the dominant Dallas fastener concern; repeated hail impacts work-harden and fatigue galvanized steel over time. Stainless-steel fasteners provide longer service in hail-corridor Dallas. Tornado-driven wind-uplift loads require specific fastener spacing on high-wind installations.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Dallas paint-compatibility considerations: 10-year re-paint cycles are standard on wood clapboard, 15-year factory-finish fiber cement ColorPlus is meaningfully longer. Hail damage to paint finish is common in DFW; post-hail paint-touch-up is typically part of insurance claim scope. Oil-based primers outperform acrylic primers on aged wood substrates. Dark colors fade measurably within 10-15 years on south and west elevations due to intense summer UV. Fluoropolymer finishes (Kynar) on fiber cement hold color 12-15 years. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Dallas insulation integration with siding replacement is moderately common under Oncor Take A Load Off Texas program envelope credits. Continuous exterior insulation (R-5 to R-8 rigid foam) outboard of sheathing plus fiber cement or vinyl reduces thermal bridging. Climate-mixed Dallas benefits from balanced U-factor and SHGC treatment rather than Phoenix-style aggressive SHGC reduction or Chicago-style aggressive U-factor reduction. Blown-cellulose cavity insulation coordinated with siding tear-off delivers additional R-value at modest incremental cost. Radiant barrier on west-facing elevations.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Dallas pressure-wash prep before siding installation: hail-damaged substrates require inspection and repair before new siding installation. 2,500-3,500 PSI pressure wash with detergent removes biological growth and loose paint. Foundation-movement-damaged siding attachments require re-shimming and fastener replacement before new material installation. Termite inspection of wood fascia and sheathing is prudent on homes over 15 years. Post-hail insurance claim scope verification should happen before any substrate preparation begins to document pre-existing condition.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Dallas siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers DFW from Texas regional office with direct installer certification support. CertainTeed operates from Shreveport LA and California plants with DFW rep coverage. LP SmartSide ships from Texas plants. Mastic (Ply Gem) handles vinyl. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple DFW locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products with same-day pickup. Wolfe Industries is regional installer supply. La Habra Stucco serves DFW stucco specialty market. All require verified city business registration for permit-pulling.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Dallas siding installer tiering: small owner-operator crews dominate older tract replacement at $7-$12 per square foot installed. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $10-$18 per square foot on fiber cement. Landmark-restoration crews with HPO expertise run $18-$32 per square foot on Munger Place, Swiss Avenue, and State-Thomas projects. DFW labor premium over national average runs 1.0-1.2x due to favorable cost of living. City of Dallas Residential Building Registration plus verified insurance is the mandatory baseline for permit-pulling.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Dallas siding upsells worth accepting: drainage-plane weather-resistive barrier behind brick veneer or fiber cement, stainless-steel fasteners on hail-corridor properties, HardieColor Plus factory finish (15-year fade warranty), and post-hail Class 4 impact-rated wall-surface products where documented. Upsells to decline: "storm-proof" proprietary products lacking documented wind-load and impact ratings, unnecessary decorative additions beyond existing facade profile, "tornado-guaranteed" vinyl claims lacking documented testing, and contractor offers to "eat your deductible" which is insurance fraud under Texas Insurance Code §4102.207.`,
    marketSizePara: `DFW metroplex has approximately 2.2 million single-family homes across Dallas, Tarrant, Collin, Denton, and Rockwall counties. Brick veneer dominates at roughly 60%, fiber cement at 18%, vinyl at 10%, stucco at 5%, and other at 7%. City of Dallas plus suburban cities pull approximately 22,000-40,000 siding permits annually across all replacement scope. Post-hail-event recovery years add substantial volume. HPO landmarked siding scope represents 3-5% of annual Dallas city total and is minimal in suburban jurisdictions.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Dallas siding pricing peaks March through June during spring-storm claim surge and optimal install conditions. July-August heat-dome surface temperatures extend project duration. October through February sees softer pricing (15-25% below peak) and faster scheduling. Winter Storm Uri-level freeze events create secondary claim surge with 6-10 week delays. Best overall combination of pricing and install conditions runs November through February. HPO review on Munger Place and Swiss Avenue often dictates scheduling more than weather.`,
  },
  "atlanta-ga": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Atlanta's dominant siding decisions split by era: wood lap siding (original and replacement) on craftsman bungalows in Virginia-Highland, Inman Park, Grant Park, and Morningside, which represents 25-35% of intown residential. Hardie fiber cement on mid-range renovations and newer tract construction in Brookhaven, Sandy Springs, Alpharetta, and East Cobb. Brick veneer on newer suburban tract construction in Gwinnett, Henry, and Forsyth counties at 40-50% of metro-wide residential. Vinyl appears on value-tier replacements but HOA restrictions in Buckhead, Morningside, and Druid Hills prohibit it.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Atlanta has 20+ designated historic districts under Atlanta Urban Design Commission (AUDC) jurisdiction including Inman Park, Grant Park, Virginia-Highland, Candler Park, Cabbagetown, Druid Hills, Ansley Park, Morningside, Reynoldstown, Adair Park, Baltimore Block, Brookwood Hills, Castleberry Hill, Hotel Row, Martin Luther King Jr. Landmark, Washington Park, West End, Westview, and Whittier Mill Village. AUDC review applies to contributing structures. Approved siding materials typically match period-appropriate wood clapboard on craftsman bungalows, brick restoration, or specific fiber cement profiles matching 1900s-1940s construction. Vinyl categorically prohibited.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `Atlanta Department of City Planning permits siding replacement through the ATLDOCS portal within 48-72 hours for straightforward replacements at $75 minimum. Fulton, DeKalb, Cobb, Gwinnett, and Clayton counties use separate permit offices. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-5 weeks. AUDC historic review adds 4-10 weeks on contributing structures. Georgia Residential Basic Contractor license required for jobs over $2,500 (verified at sos.ga.gov). Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (many intown craftsman bungalows) trigger EPA RRP scope. Pollen-season (February-March) protocols affect active work sites.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Atlanta has no coastal saltwater exposure; corrosion concerns center on Georgia red-clay soil movement that stresses framing and siding seams. Termite infestation of wood fascia, soffits, and siding is the dominant Atlanta deterioration concern; wood siding at grade-level elevations requires pressure-treated framing or fiber cement substitution. Galvanized steel fasteners perform adequately in Atlanta's inland climate. Humidity-driven biological growth (mildew, algae, mold) on north-facing elevations is severe; zinc or copper trim components reduce biological growth but add cost.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Atlanta paint-compatibility considerations: 7-12 year re-paint cycles are standard on wood clapboard due to Piedmont humidity and UV, 15-year factory-finish fiber cement ColorPlus is meaningfully longer. Mildew-resistant paint additives are essential; Benjamin Moore Aura exterior, Sherwin-Williams Duration with mildew resistance, and Behr Premium Plus Ultra are Atlanta-proven. Pollen-season (February-March) coats active paint work and requires specific timing coordination. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (most intown craftsman bungalows) trigger EPA RRP scope. Pollen wash-down before paint application is Atlanta-specific protocol.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Atlanta insulation integration with siding replacement is common under Georgia Power Home Energy Improvement Program rebates. Continuous exterior insulation (R-5 to R-8 rigid foam) outboard of sheathing plus fiber cement reduces thermal bridging in humid-subtropical Atlanta climate. Spray foam on wood-framed siding substrates provides moisture resistance plus thermal improvement. Humidity management behind siding is the critical Atlanta assembly-design factor; drainage-plane weather-resistive barrier with proper flashing prevents moisture accumulation. Vapor-open assemblies perform well in Atlanta climate.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Atlanta pressure-wash prep before siding installation: heavy humidity-driven biological growth requires aggressive cleaning before new siding installation. 2,500-3,500 PSI pressure wash with bleach-based detergent (3-5% sodium hypochlorite solution) is Atlanta standard. Termite inspection of wood fascia and sheathing before installation is essential; termite-damaged structural wood must be replaced before new siding installation. Pollen-season (February-March) site cleaning is Atlanta-specific before any exterior paint or siding work. Pressure-wash contamination of adjacent surfaces requires careful drainage-plane coordination.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Atlanta siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Atlanta from Atlanta regional office (Hardie has strong SE presence). CertainTeed operates from Atlanta and Roanoke VA plants. LP SmartSide ships from regional distribution. Mastic (Ply Gem) handles vinyl. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple Atlanta locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products with same-day pickup. Ply Gem handles vinyl distribution. Atlanta is a major SE distribution hub; lead times to Atlanta are favorable for all major brands (1-3 days stock, 2-5 days custom).`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Atlanta siding installer tiering: small owner-operator crews dominate suburban vinyl and entry-tier fiber cement at $8-$13 per square foot installed. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $11-$19 per square foot on fiber cement. AUDC landmark-restoration crews run $20-$38 per square foot on Inman Park, Virginia-Highland, and Druid Hills projects. Atlanta labor premium over national average runs 1.0-1.3x. Georgia Residential Basic Contractor license plus workers' compensation and general liability certificates are the verifiable baseline. Small crews may lack state license but hold county registrations.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Atlanta siding upsells worth accepting: drainage-plane weather-resistive barrier (critical in Piedmont humidity), pressure-treated or fiber-cement-substitute at grade-level (termite resistance), HardieColor Plus factory finish (15-year fade warranty), mildew-resistant paint additives, and zinc or copper trim on humidity-exposed elevations. Upsells to decline: "Southern-specific" proprietary products without documented biological-growth testing, unnecessary decorative additions beyond existing facade profile, cedar shingle or shake in Atlanta humidity (degrades faster than most markets), and AOB (Assignment of Benefits) signing on insurance claims (10-day rescission window under O.C.G.A. §33-24-59.25).`,
    marketSizePara: `Atlanta metro (Fulton, DeKalb, Cobb, Gwinnett, Clayton, Cherokee, Douglas, Fayette, Forsyth, Henry, Rockdale counties) has approximately 1.8 million single-family homes. Brick veneer dominates at roughly 45%, fiber cement at 20%, wood lap siding at 15%, vinyl at 12%, and other at 8%. Atlanta Department of City Planning plus suburban counties pulls approximately 18,000-32,000 siding permits annually across all replacement scope. AUDC landmarked siding scope represents 3-5% of annual Atlanta city total. Humidity-driven maintenance repaints are often permitted as maintenance rather than replacement.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Atlanta siding pricing peaks March through June during optimal install conditions between pollen season and summer humidity extremes, plus spring-storm claim surge. Pollen season (February-March) coats active work sites and discourages some installers from scheduling. July-August humidity and thunderstorm frequency disrupt install windows. October through December sees softer pricing (10-18% below peak) and faster scheduling. Best overall combination of pricing and install conditions runs October-November and April. AUDC review on Inman Park and Virginia-Highland often dictates scheduling more than weather.`,
  },
  "denver-co": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Denver's dominant siding material is fiber cement (James Hardie HardiePlank) on mid-range tract construction and higher-end renovations in Wash Park, Highlands, Stapleton, and Cherry Creek, which represents 25-35% of metro-wide residential. Stucco on Spanish-influenced homes in Country Club and Cherry Creek. Wood lap siding on landmarked Capitol Hill, Country Club, and Baker historic homes. Vinyl on value-tier tract construction in Aurora, Arvada, and outer Adams County. Cedar shingle and shake on architect-designed mountain-contemporary builds in foothill-adjacent neighborhoods.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Denver has 55+ designated landmark districts under Denver Landmark Preservation Commission jurisdiction including Capitol Hill, Country Club, Baker, Humboldt Street, Wyman, Witter-Cofield, Swallow Hill, Curtis Park, Five Points, Highland, Potter Highlands, Packard's Hill, Quality Hill, Larimer Square, Lower Downtown (LoDo), Clements, Fisher Arch, Montclair, Park Hill, Harman, and Ninth Street Historic District. Landmark review applies to contributing structures. Approved siding materials typically include period-appropriate wood clapboard, brick restoration, or specific stucco matching 1880s-1920s Queen Anne and Victorian construction.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `Denver Development Services permits siding replacement through the ePermit portal within 48-72 hours for straightforward replacements at $95 minimum. Arapahoe, Jefferson, Adams, Douglas counties use separate permit processes. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-5 weeks. Denver Landmark historic review adds 4-10 weeks on contributing structures. Denver Class D (residential) Supervisor License required for permit-pulling (Colorado has no statewide residential contractor license). High-altitude construction (>5,000 feet elevation) requires specific assembly detail. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Denver has no coastal saltwater exposure; corrosion concerns center on hail-driven fastener and aluminum component damage. Class 4 impact-rated fiber cement and vinyl products provide measurable hail-damage resistance. High-altitude UV at 5,280 feet accelerates color fading and paint-film degradation across all materials; south and west elevations show measurable fade within 8-12 years. Mountain-adjacent properties see wind-driven debris damage during chinook events. Stainless-steel fasteners outperform galvanized in freeze-thaw cycling over 15-25 year service life.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Denver paint-compatibility considerations: high-altitude UV exposure at 5,280 feet elevation is particularly hard on paint film; 10-year re-paint cycles are standard on wood clapboard, 15-year factory-finish fiber cement ColorPlus is meaningfully longer. Dark colors fade measurably within 8-12 years on south and west elevations. Fluoropolymer finishes (Kynar 500, Fluoropon) on fiber cement hold color 12-15 years and justify the 25% premium in high-altitude Denver UV. Oil-based primers outperform acrylic primers on aged wood substrates in Denver climate. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Denver insulation integration with siding replacement is heavily incentivized under Xcel Energy Solar*Rewards and R2E2 state program. Continuous exterior insulation (R-8 to R-15 rigid foam or mineral wool) outboard of sheathing plus fiber cement dramatically reduces thermal bridging in cold-dry Denver climate. Denver Green Code (voluntary but increasingly referenced) and 2021 IECC mandate continuous air barrier testing on whole-home retrofits. R-20+ total wall assembly performance meets Denver Stretch Code. Blower-door testing verifies air-tightness on conservation-improvement-funded jobs.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Denver pressure-wash prep before siding installation: hail-damaged substrates require full inspection and repair before new siding installation. 2,500-3,500 PSI pressure wash with detergent removes biological growth and loose paint. Post-hail insurance claim scope verification should happen before substrate preparation to document pre-existing condition. High-altitude UV-degraded paint film requires aggressive removal before new paint or finish application. Freeze-thaw-damaged substrates require moisture testing using moisture meter to identify hidden sheathing damage.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Denver siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Denver from Rocky Mountain regional office with direct installer certification support. CertainTeed operates from Shakopee MN and California plants with Denver rep coverage. LP SmartSide ships from Midwest plants with 3-5 day lead times. Mastic (Ply Gem) handles vinyl. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple Denver locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products with same-day pickup. Denver is a moderate-volume distribution market; lead times to Denver are favorable for all major brands.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Denver siding installer tiering: small owner-operator crews dominate suburban vinyl and entry-tier fiber cement at $9-$15 per square foot installed. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $12-$21 per square foot on fiber cement. Denver Landmark-restoration crews run $22-$42 per square foot on Capitol Hill, Country Club, and Baker projects. Denver labor premium over national average runs 1.1-1.3x. Denver Class D Supervisor License plus insurance certificates are the verifiable baseline for permit-pulling. Out-of-state storm-chase crews after major hail events are the highest-risk Denver contractor category.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Denver siding upsells worth accepting: Class 4 impact-rated fiber cement on hail-corridor properties (5-10% insurance premium reduction), continuous exterior insulation (R-8+ rigid foam or mineral wool for cold-dry Denver climate), HardieColor Plus factory finish with UV-stabilized fluoropolymer on south and west elevations, and high-altitude-specific fastener selection. Upsells to decline: "altitude-specific" proprietary products without documented UL or ASTM certification, unnecessary decorative additions beyond existing facade profile, and builder-grade thin-gauge vinyl in hail-corridor climate (typically fails at first major hail event).`,
    marketSizePara: `Denver metro (Denver, Arapahoe, Jefferson, Adams, Douglas, Boulder, Broomfield, Elbert counties) has approximately 1.4 million single-family homes. Brick veneer dominates at roughly 40%, fiber cement at 22%, vinyl at 15%, stucco at 10%, wood at 6%, and other at 7%. Denver Development Services plus suburban counties pull approximately 14,000-25,000 siding permits annually across all replacement scope. Post-hail recovery years add substantial volume (2017, 2023 events drove 40,000+ annual permits). Denver Landmark landmarked siding scope represents 2-4% of annual city total.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Denver siding pricing peaks April through October during optimal install conditions and post-hail claim surge. June-July hail season can compress scheduling to 10-16 week backlogs after major outbreak events. November through March sub-freezing ambient compromises vinyl impact resistance and caulk activation; most Denver contractors stop work when temperatures drop below 32F. Fiber cement can install in cold weather with proper primer but labor premiums run 20-30% from December through February. Best pricing typically runs May and September-October (10-18% below peak).`,
  },
  "seattle-wa": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Seattle's dominant siding material is cedar clapboard and cedar shake on 1910s-1950s craftsman and Tudor homes across Capitol Hill, Ballard, Wallingford, Queen Anne, and Madrona. Fiber cement (James Hardie HardiePlank) on modern renovations and mid-century box homes in Wedgwood, View Ridge, and Sand Point. Vinyl appears on value-tier installations but Seattle's aesthetic tradition and HOA restrictions in Laurelhurst, Broadmoor, and Madrona discourage it. Cedar siding is the Seattle signature material, and cedar that has been properly maintained or restored commands premium resale value.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Seattle has 8 designated historic districts and 450+ individually landmarked properties under Seattle Landmarks Preservation Board jurisdiction including Pike Place Market, Pioneer Square, Harvard-Belmont, Ballard Avenue, Columbia City, Fort Lawton Landmark District, International District, and Sand Point Naval Air Station. Individually landmarked homes appear across Queen Anne, Capitol Hill, Madrona, Mount Baker, and Washington Park. Landmark review applies to contributing structures. Approved siding materials typically include cedar clapboard matching original profile, cedar shake, or specific composition profiles matching 1890s-1930s construction.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `Seattle Department of Construction and Inspections (SDCI) permits siding replacement through the Accela portal within 5-10 business days at $180 minimum. King County unincorporated uses separate permits with similar timelines. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-6 weeks. Seattle Landmark historic review adds 4-12 weeks on contributing structures. Washington L&I contractor registration mandatory for permit-pulling. Seattle Energy Code amendments require specific wall assembly performance and continuous air-barrier testing on major renovations. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Seattle coastal zones (West Seattle, Magnolia, Alki, Elliott Bay-facing properties) experience significant salt-air corrosion on fasteners and aluminum trim components. Stainless steel 304 or 316 fasteners are the durable Seattle coastal spec; galvanized steel pits within 5-7 years in Puget Sound salt-spray environments. Marine-coated aluminum or copper are coastal-durable trim materials. Cascadia earthquake preparation drives interest in laminated window glazing retention, which coordinates with siding-integration detail. Waterfront properties in Seattle see sustained marine moisture exposure year-round.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Seattle paint-compatibility considerations: cedar requires specific cedar-compatible stains or semi-transparent finishes (Cabot, Sikkens, Superdeck) every 5-7 years in Seattle moisture environment. Opaque paint on cedar tends to trap moisture and accelerate substrate rot; transparent or semi-transparent finishes allow moisture movement. Mildew-resistant additives are essential. Oil-based primers outperform acrylic primers on aged cedar in Seattle marine climate. Fiber cement factory finish (HardieColor Plus) delivers 15-year fade warranty. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (majority of Seattle craftsman and Tudor stock) trigger EPA RRP.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Seattle insulation integration with siding replacement is incentivized under Seattle City Light Energy Smart plus Puget Sound Energy Home Weatherization Rebate. Continuous exterior insulation (R-5 to R-10 rigid foam or mineral wool) outboard of sheathing plus cedar or fiber cement reduces thermal bridging in marine cool Seattle climate. Seattle Energy Code (2021) requires specific wall assembly performance and continuous air-barrier testing. Vapor-open assemblies with exterior-side mineral wool perform well in Seattle's high-moisture climate; vapor-closed assemblies can trap moisture in wall cavities.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Seattle pressure-wash prep before siding installation: heavy biological growth (moss, algae, mildew) on cedar and fiber cement substrates requires aggressive cleaning before new installation. 1,500-2,500 PSI pressure wash with bleach-based detergent (3-5% sodium hypochlorite) removes surface growth; higher pressure damages cedar fiber. Hidden-rot concealment is the dominant Seattle fraud pattern; probe framing and sheathing behind existing siding during initial assessment. Seattle landmark properties require specific cedar-cleaning protocols to preserve aged patina.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Seattle siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Seattle from Pacific Northwest regional office. CertainTeed operates from California plants with Seattle rep coverage. LP SmartSide ships from regional distribution. Cedar Shake & Shingle Bureau certifies installers on Western Red Cedar. Cedar Valley Shingles (WA), Watkins Sawmills (BC), and Teal-Jones Group (BC) supply cedar with 1-2 week lead times. Local distributors include ABC Supply, Beacon Building Products (Kent, Everett), and Pacific Supply with same-day or next-day pickup. Washington L&I registration mandatory and publicly searchable.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Seattle siding installer tiering: cedar-specialty crews with Cedar Shake & Shingle Bureau certification run $18-$32 per square foot installed on cedar clapboard or shake (this is a specialty skill set). Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $14-$24 per square foot on fiber cement. Seattle Landmarks-restoration crews run $25-$48 per square foot on Queen Anne, Capitol Hill, and Madrona landmarked projects. Seattle labor premium over national average runs 1.3-1.6x due to high cost of living. Washington L&I registration plus bond status matching job scope is the verifiable baseline.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Seattle siding upsells worth accepting: cedar-specific stain or semi-transparent finish rather than opaque paint (allows moisture movement), zinc or copper trim on biological-growth-exposed elevations (reduces moss by 60-80%), continuous exterior insulation (R-5+ rigid foam or mineral wool), and stainless-steel fasteners on coastal-adjacent properties. Upsells to decline: opaque paint on cedar (traps moisture and accelerates rot), "Seattle-specific" proprietary products lacking independent testing, covering hidden rot without repair (dominant local fraud pattern), and vinyl siding that violates most Seattle-market HOA restrictions.`,
    marketSizePara: `Seattle metro (King, Pierce, Snohomish, Kitsap counties) has approximately 1.1 million single-family homes. Fiber cement and cedar dominate at roughly 50% combined, vinyl at 15%, brick veneer at 12%, stucco at 8%, and other at 15%. Seattle SDCI plus suburban cities pull approximately 8,000-15,000 siding permits annually across all replacement scope. Seattle Landmark landmarked siding scope represents 2-4% of annual total. Cedar restoration projects are often permitted as maintenance rather than replacement, so permit data understates actual volume.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Seattle siding pricing peaks June through September during the reliable dry-weather install window. October through April sustained precipitation disrupts install scheduling; most Seattle contractors stop siding work during atmospheric-river storms and reschedule to next available dry window. This compresses peak-season demand into 4 months, making summer bookings competitive (8-14 week lead times common). May and late September are the sweet spot for pricing and scheduling. Winter (November-March) is feasible only for covered or protected scope; labor premiums run 25-40% above peak season.`,
  },
  "austin-tx": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Austin's dominant siding material is limestone veneer on West Austin homes in Westlake, Rollingwood, Barton Creek, and Lost Creek, which represents 15-25% of metro-wide residential. Hardie fiber cement on mid-range renovations and newer tract construction in Mueller, Circle C, and Southwest Hills. Brick veneer on newer suburban tract construction in Williamson and Hays counties. Stucco on Mediterranean-style homes scattered across West Austin. Vinyl is uncommon due to limestone aesthetic tradition and HOA restrictions in most newer developments. Wood clapboard on landmarked Hyde Park and Travis Heights bungalows.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Austin has 8 locally designated historic districts and 20+ National Register-listed districts under Historic Landmark Commission (HLC) jurisdiction including Hyde Park, Travis Heights, Clarksville, Old West Austin, Rainey Street Historic District, Judges Hill, Robertson Hill, West Line, East Austin MLK, Willow-Spence, Palm Memorial School, North Austin, Swedish Hill, Smoot-Terrace Park, East Avenue, Harris Ridge, and Swede Hill. HLC review applies to contributing structures. Approved siding materials typically include period-appropriate wood clapboard matching original profile on bungalow-era homes, limestone restoration, or specific fiber cement profiles matching 1900s-1940s construction.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `Austin Development Services Department permits siding replacement through the AB+C Portal within 48-72 hours for straightforward replacements at $85 minimum. Travis, Williamson, and Hays counties use separate permit offices. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-5 weeks. HLC historic review adds 4-8 weeks on contributing structures. City of Austin Registered Residential Building Contractor status required for permit-pulling (Texas has no state license). Limestone-faced Westlake and Rollingwood homes require specialty masonry-prep detail. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Austin has no coastal saltwater exposure; corrosion concerns center on Hill Country thermal cycling and Uri-style freeze-shock events. Uri 2021 freeze-crack damage to vinyl and thin-gauge fiber cement drove Texas insurance claim surge. Stainless-steel fasteners outperform galvanized in Austin's thermal cycling and hail exposure. Limestone-faced homes in Westlake require specific non-corrosive hardware to avoid stone mortar staining. Freeze-crack resistance on siding materials is a post-Uri spec-selection factor; thicker fiber cement (7/16" nominal) outperforms thin-gauge material.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Austin paint-compatibility considerations: 10-year re-paint cycles are standard on wood clapboard due to Hill Country UV, 15-year factory-finish fiber cement ColorPlus is meaningfully longer. Dark colors fade measurably within 8-12 years on south and west elevations due to 230+ sunny days annually. Fluoropolymer finishes (Kynar, Fluoropon) on fiber cement hold color 12-15 years. Oil-based primers outperform acrylic primers on aged wood substrates. Post-Uri 2021 freeze-cracked paint film often requires full refinish rather than touch-up. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Austin insulation integration with siding replacement is common under Austin Energy Rebates program (up to $0.75 per square foot of glass area on qualifying envelope work). Continuous exterior insulation (R-5 to R-8 rigid foam) outboard of sheathing plus fiber cement reduces thermal bridging in hot-humid Austin climate. Austin Energy Code (2022) requires specific wall assembly performance and cool-roof reflectance on low-slope portions of residential. Radiant barrier on west-facing wall elevations reduces solar gain. Spray foam cavity insulation coordinated with siding tear-off adds additional R-value at modest cost.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Austin pressure-wash prep before siding installation: biological growth on north-facing elevations (less severe than Atlanta or Houston but present) requires cleaning before new siding installation. 2,000-3,000 PSI pressure wash with detergent. Post-Uri 2021 thermal-shock crack inspection before substrate prep identifies freeze-damage requiring repair. Termite inspection of wood fascia and sheathing before installation is prudent. Limestone-faced homes require gentle cleaning protocols (1,000-1,500 PSI) to avoid mortar damage. Hill Country live-oak debris and pollen accumulation may require additional rinse-down before paint or finish application.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Austin siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Austin from Texas regional office with direct installer certification support. CertainTeed operates from Shreveport LA and California plants. LP SmartSide ships from Texas plants. Mastic (Ply Gem) handles vinyl. Limestone supply comes from regional Hill Country quarries (Williamson County, Burnet County). Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple Austin locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products with same-day pickup. Austin Stone Supply is regional limestone specialty supplier.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Austin siding installer tiering: small owner-operator crews dominate suburban vinyl and entry-tier fiber cement at $8-$14 per square foot installed. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $11-$20 per square foot on fiber cement. Limestone-specialty masons run $22-$42 per square foot on Westlake, Rollingwood, and Barton Creek projects. HLC landmark-restoration crews run $20-$38 per square foot on Hyde Park and Travis Heights projects. Austin labor premium over national average runs 1.1-1.4x due to rapid growth. City of Austin Registered Residential Building Contractor status is mandatory baseline.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Austin siding upsells worth accepting: thicker 7/16" fiber cement over thin-gauge (post-Uri freeze resistance), HardieColor Plus factory finish (15-year fade warranty), stainless-steel fasteners on Hill Country thermal-cycling exposure, and Austin Energy cool-reflectance coatings on west-facing elevations. Upsells to decline: "Hill Country-specific" proprietary products lacking documented testing, unnecessary decorative additions beyond existing facade profile, "Uri-proof" vinyl claims lacking independent freeze-shock testing, and builder-grade thin-gauge vinyl that cracked widely during Uri 2021 event.`,
    marketSizePara: `Austin metro (Travis, Williamson, Hays, Bastrop, Caldwell counties) has approximately 720,000 single-family homes as of 2026 (rapid 4-6% annual growth). Brick veneer dominates at roughly 45%, fiber cement at 22%, limestone veneer at 10%, stucco at 8%, vinyl at 6%, and other at 9%. City of Austin Development Services plus suburban counties pull approximately 10,000-20,000 siding permits annually across all replacement scope. Rapid growth drives new-construction share above typical US metros. HLC landmarked siding scope represents 2-3% of annual total.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Austin siding pricing peaks March through June during spring-storm claim surge and optimal install conditions. July-August heat-dome surface temperatures extend project duration. October through February sees softer pricing (15-25% below peak) and faster scheduling. Post-Uri 2021 freeze events created secondary claim surge with 6-10 week delays. Best overall combination of pricing and install conditions runs October-November and February-March (before pollen peak). HLC review on Hyde Park and Travis Heights often dictates scheduling more than weather.`,
  },
  "san-francisco-ca": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `SF's dominant siding material is wood siding on Victorian and Edwardian painted ladies across Alamo Square, Pacific Heights, Haight-Ashbury, Noe Valley, and Bernal Heights. Stucco on Sunset and Richmond District 1930s-1950s row houses (which represents 35-45% of SF housing stock). Custom specialty materials on architect-designed Mid-Century and Modern homes in Forest Hill, St. Francis Wood, and Twin Peaks. Vinyl is categorically prohibited in SF historic preservation districts and rare even outside protected areas. Cedar and redwood are Victorian-era originals; restoration uses matching clear-vertical-grain material.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `San Francisco has 270+ designated landmarks under Article 10 plus 11 historic districts under Article 11 of Planning Code. Districts include Alamo Square, Jackson Square, Liberty-Hill, Dogpatch, Chinatown, Webster Street, Willis Polk Residences, Bush Street-Cottage Row, Northeast Waterfront, and South End. Individually landmarked buildings across Pacific Heights, Presidio Heights, Nob Hill, Russian Hill, Telegraph Hill, North Beach, Haight-Ashbury, and Noe Valley. Landmark review requires wood true-historic-profile matching on contributing structures. Approved siding materials typically include original-matching redwood, cedar, or specific composition profiles.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `San Francisco Department of Building Inspection (DBI) permits siding replacement through the Permit Center within 5-10 business days at $285 minimum. Scope changes trigger Plan Check review adding 2-6 weeks. SF Historic Preservation Commission review on landmarked properties adds 6-14 weeks. California CSLB license mandatory (C-35 plastering for stucco, C-6 cabinet/millwork for wood, or B general). SF DBI additionally requires city contractor registration. SF dust-control ordinance §3428 requires HEPA-vacuum cleanup verification; pre-1978 homes require EPA RRP certification.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `SF coastal zones (Pacifica-adjacent, Ocean Beach, Twin Peaks, Presidio-adjacent) experience significant salt-air corrosion on fasteners and aluminum trim. Stainless steel 304 or 316 fasteners are the durable SF coastal spec; galvanized steel pits within 5-7 years in Pacific fog-belt salt environments. Marine-coated aluminum or copper trim is coastal-durable. California Coastal Commission jurisdiction adds permit complexity on Coastal Zone properties. Fog-belt microclimate (Sunset, Richmond) sees sustained moisture exposure year-round; sun-belt microclimate (Mission, Bernal, Potrero) sees minimal moisture but more UV.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `SF paint-compatibility considerations: Victorian painted ladies require specific color-accurate restoration using period-appropriate palettes (Benjamin Moore Historical, Sherwin-Williams Preservation, Farrow & Ball Archive). Multi-color trim schemes require specialist painters; painted ladies restoration typically runs $45,000-$120,000 on a full exterior. 6-10 year re-paint cycles on Victorian painted ladies due to fog-belt humidity and color complexity. Oil-based primers outperform acrylic on aged redwood and cedar. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (vast majority of SF Victorian and Edwardian stock) trigger EPA RRP.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `SF insulation integration with siding replacement is incentivized under PG&E Home Efficiency Rebate Plus plus BayREN Home+ incentives. Continuous exterior insulation (R-5 to R-10 rigid foam or mineral wool) outboard of sheathing reduces thermal bridging. Title 24 Part 6 (2022) requires specific wall assembly performance on major renovations. Seismic retrofitting under SF Mandatory Soft-Story Retrofit Program (Administrative Code §34B) coordinates with siding scope on ground-floor elevations; structural engineer involvement required.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `SF pressure-wash prep before siding installation: biological growth on north-facing and fog-belt elevations requires aggressive cleaning before new siding installation. 1,500-2,500 PSI pressure wash with bleach-based detergent on stucco; gentler 1,000-1,500 PSI on aged Victorian redwood to avoid fiber damage. Victorian restoration projects require specific cleaning protocols to preserve aged patina and original molding detail. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (nearly all SF Victorian) trigger EPA RRP with HEPA-vacuum containment. Hidden-rot probe of framing behind existing siding during initial assessment.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `SF siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers SF from California regional office. CertainTeed operates from California plants. LP SmartSide ships from regional distribution. La Habra Stucco serves SF stucco market. Cedar and redwood for Victorian restoration typically come from specialty mills: Mendocino Redwood Company (CA), Humboldt Redwood Company (CA), Pacific Rim Cedar (OR/WA). Local distributors include ABC Supply, Beacon Building Products (Brisbane, San Jose), and Dunn-Edwards Supply with same-day pickup. Victorian hardware from specialty restoration suppliers.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `SF siding installer tiering: stucco specialty crews (C-35 plastering license) run $14-$24 per square foot on 3-coat stucco in Sunset and Richmond. Victorian restoration crews with specialty expertise run $38-$85 per square foot on painted ladies (this is specialty historic restoration work). Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $18-$32 per square foot on fiber cement. SF labor premium over national average runs 1.8-2.5x due to very high cost of living and specialty restoration expertise. Active CSLB license plus SF DBI city contractor registration are the verifiable baseline.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `SF siding upsells worth accepting: true-historic-profile wood matching on landmarked Victorian restoration, drainage-plane weather-resistive barrier (critical in fog-belt moisture), stainless-steel fasteners on coastal-adjacent properties, and seismic-retrofit coordination on soft-story addresses. Upsells to decline: off-the-shelf fiber cement substitution for true-historic-profile on landmarked elevations (SF HPC catches mismatches at inspection), "Victorian-specific" proprietary products without historic-preservation approval, and unnecessary decorative additions beyond original facade profile. Victorian restoration is specialty work; off-the-shelf products fail review.`,
    marketSizePara: `San Francisco city and county has approximately 180,000 residential structures. Stucco dominates SF at roughly 45% (Sunset and Richmond row houses), wood at 30% (Victorian and Edwardian), fiber cement at 10%, and other at 15%. SF Bay Area metro (SF, San Mateo, Marin, Alameda, Contra Costa, Santa Clara counties) totals approximately 1.7 million residential units. SF DBI pulls approximately 3,500-6,500 siding permits annually; Bay Area metro runs 35,000-55,000. SF Historic Preservation Commission landmarked siding scope represents 5-8% of annual SF city total (significantly higher than most metros).`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `San Francisco siding pricing peaks June through October during the reliable dry-weather install window. November through March atmospheric-river rainfall disrupts install scheduling; most SF contractors stop siding work during major rain events and reschedule. This compresses peak-season demand into 5 months, making summer bookings competitive (10-18 week lead times common for July-September slots). April-May and late October are the sweet spot for pricing. Winter (December-February) is feasible only for protected scope; labor premiums run 20-35% above peak season. Coastal Commission permitting dictates timing on coastal-zone properties.`,
  },
  "las-vegas-nv": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Vegas's dominant siding material is 3-coat stucco on master-planned community construction in Summerlin, Henderson, Green Valley, Anthem, MacDonald Ranch, and Seven Hills, which dominates at 80-85% of residential. Fiber cement (James Hardie HardiePlank) appears on higher-end architect-designed homes. Vinyl and wood siding are rare due to extreme UV degradation and HOA prohibitions. John S. Park and Huntridge historic areas have wood lap siding on 1940s-1960s homes requiring specialty maintenance. 3-coat stucco (scratch, brown, finish) over paper-and-lath requires re-coat every 10-15 years due to UV fade.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Las Vegas has limited historic designation compared to older US metros. The John S. Park Historic District (downtown, 1930s-1950s residential) and Huntridge Historic District (1940s-1960s) are the primary protected areas under City of Las Vegas Historic Preservation Commission. West Las Vegas (historically African-American community dating to 1905) has National Register listings but minimal local-level design review. Boulder City maintains its own historic district with stricter design review. Landmark review where applicable requires matching original siding profile on contributing structures; stucco texture-matching and specific wood profile restoration.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `Clark County Building Department permits residential siding replacement through the online portal within 48-72 hours for straightforward replacements at $75 minimum. City of Las Vegas, Henderson, North Las Vegas, and Boulder City use separate permit processes. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-4 weeks. HPC historic review adds 4-8 weeks on contributing John S. Park or Huntridge structures. HOA architectural approval in Summerlin, Anthem, MacDonald Ranch, and Seven Hills is often more time-consuming than county permit. Nevada C-17 plastering license required for stucco work; C-B General Building for broader scope.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Vegas has no coastal saltwater exposure but monsoon-season dust-storm debris and Mojave blowing dust abrade stucco finish. Dust-storm debris removal annually prevents accelerated paint-film degradation. Fastener corrosion is minimal in dry desert climate; galvanized steel performs adequately for 25-30 year service life. Monsoon-driven microburst damage to siding (particularly stucco crack propagation) is the dominant Vegas weather-driven concern. UV degradation is the dominant durability factor: unprotected paint chalks within 4-6 years, vinyl degrades within 8-12 years, dark stucco fades within 6-10 years.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Vegas paint-compatibility considerations: stucco color refresh typically runs 10-15 year cycles with elastomeric re-coat rather than paint-over. Elastomeric coatings (Dunn-Edwards Enduracoat, Frazee, Sherwin-Williams Duration) provide crack-bridging and UV resistance at 12-18 year service. Dark colors fade measurably within 6-10 years on south and west elevations due to extreme Vegas UV. Fluoropolymer finishes (Kynar, Fluoropon) on fiber cement hold color 10-13 years in Vegas UV. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (concentrated in John S. Park and Huntridge) trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Vegas insulation integration with siding replacement is common on framed (non-block-wall) construction under NV Energy envelope credit program. Continuous exterior insulation (R-5 to R-8 rigid foam) outboard of sheathing plus stucco or fiber cement reduces thermal bridging in cooling-dominated Vegas climate. Block-wall construction provides thermal mass; insulation retrofits typically use interior furring and batt rather than exterior rigid foam. Radiant barrier on wall assembly reduces solar gain on west-facing elevations. Clark County energy code requires specific reflectance on new construction; alterations less strictly governed.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Vegas pressure-wash prep before siding installation: stucco repair requires moisture testing first using moisture meter. Scope documentation and proper 3-coat application over new paper-and-lath in damaged areas is legitimate protocol. Dust-storm particulate buildup on wall surfaces requires aggressive cleaning before new finish. 2,500-3,500 PSI pressure wash with detergent. HOA architectural approval may require specific stucco color matching before recoat. Summer heat makes pressure-wash scheduling difficult; most Vegas contractors clean at dawn and dry before noon in June-September.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Vegas siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Vegas from California regional office. CertainTeed operates from California plants with Vegas rep coverage. LP SmartSide ships from regional distribution. La Habra Stucco (La Habra CA) is dominant regional stucco manufacturer. Kelley Manufacturing provides Vegas stucco supply. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple Vegas locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products with same-day pickup. Nevada C-17 plastering license and C-B General Building license are mandatory and publicly searchable at nscb.nv.gov.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Vegas siding installer tiering: small owner-operator stucco-specialty crews dominate residential repair and recoat at $4-$8 per square foot on single-coat elastomeric or $7-$13 per square foot on 3-coat. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $9-$16 per square foot on fiber cement. HPC landmark-restoration crews run $16-$28 per square foot on John S. Park and Huntridge projects. Vegas labor premium over national average runs 0.9-1.2x due to favorable cost of living. NRS §624.6245 caps contractor deposits at 10% of contract or $1,000; any Vegas contract demanding more is unenforceable.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Vegas siding upsells worth accepting: elastomeric crack-bridging coating on recoat (prevents monsoon moisture intrusion), UV-stabilized fluoropolymer finish on fiber cement (Kynar/Fluoropon, 10-13 year color warranty), stainless-steel fasteners on monsoon-exposed elevations, and light-colored finishes on west-facing elevations (reduces solar gain). Upsells to decline: "desert-specific" proprietary products without documented UV testing, quickie elastomeric patches over cracked stucco without moisture testing, unnecessary decorative additions beyond existing facade profile, and HOA-required recoat with surface-only treatment that ignores underlying damage.`,
    marketSizePara: `Las Vegas metro (Clark County primarily, plus Nye County) has approximately 780,000 single-family homes. Stucco dominates at roughly 80% (driven by master-planned community construction), fiber cement at 8%, vinyl at 5%, brick veneer at 3%, and other at 4%. Clark County pulls approximately 12,000-22,000 siding permits annually; Vegas's rapid housing growth (3-5% annual) drives significant new-construction share of total permits. HPC landmarked siding scope represents minimal share of annual total (John S. Park and Huntridge have limited total parcel count).`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Vegas siding pricing peaks November through April during snowbird-season demand and comfortable-ambient install conditions. May through September surface temperatures restrict stucco cure and fiber cement installation to early-morning hours. Monsoon-season rain events from July through September further disrupt install windows. Best pricing is typically June-September (20-30% below peak) with the caveat that active install scheduling is very difficult. November through February is the optimal combination of pricing and install conditions for most Vegas siding work. HOA ARC review cycles dictate scheduling more than weather.`,
  },
  "philadelphia-pa": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Philadelphia's dominant siding material is brick masonry on rowhouse trinity and three-story twin housing across Center City, South Philly, Northern Liberties, Fishtown, and Kensington, which dominates at 60-70% of Philly residential. Hardie fiber cement and wood lap siding appear on framed sections (gables, dormers) and on Northwest Philadelphia single-family homes in Chestnut Hill, Mount Airy, Germantown, and East Oak Lane. Vinyl on value-tier installations in outer neighborhoods. Philadelphia brick requires tuckpointing and repointing rather than replacement; most Philly siding work happens on framed elevations.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Philadelphia has 18,000+ historic structures and 20+ designated historic districts under Philadelphia Historical Commission jurisdiction including Society Hill, Old City, Rittenhouse, Chestnut Hill, Germantown, Powelton Village, Queen Village, Fairmount Park, Girard Estate, University City, Washington Square West, Spring Garden, Parkside, West Philadelphia Streetcar Suburb, East Falls, Logan Square, Spruce Hill, Tioga, and Fitler Square. Landmark review applies to contributing structures. Approved siding materials typically include brick restoration, period-appropriate wood clapboard, or specific stucco matching 1700s-1920s rowhouse and single-family patterns.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `Philadelphia Department of Licenses and Inspections (L&I) permits residential siding replacement through the ePLAN portal within 5-7 business days at $150 minimum. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-6 weeks. Philadelphia Historical Commission review adds 6-12 weeks on landmarked properties. Pennsylvania HICPA registration plus Philadelphia city Contractor License both required on contract. Rowhouse scaffolding permits through PDE for adjacent-property access add 2-3 weeks. Asbestos in pre-1980 cladding requires PA DEP notification. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (vast majority of Philly rowhouses) trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Philadelphia has no coastal saltwater exposure; corrosion concerns center on Delaware River flood-zone humidity and winter road-salt spray. Philadelphia Department of Streets and Sanitation winter salt-spray across Center City and South Philly corrodes fasteners and aluminum trim within 5-7 years on uncoated galvanized steel. Stainless steel 304 fasteners outperform galvanized. Flood-zone properties in Old City, Port Richmond, and Pennsport require specific flood-resistant detailing. Rowhouse party-wall drainage coordination is critical; failed counter-flashing at party walls is the #1 rowhouse failure mode.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Philadelphia paint-compatibility considerations: 8-12 year re-paint cycles on wood clapboard, 15-year factory-finish fiber cement ColorPlus is meaningfully longer. Rowhouse front facades facing south and west require higher-UV-resistance paint. Oil-based primers outperform acrylic on aged wood. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (nearly all Philly rowhouses) trigger EPA RRP scope. Brick repointing uses specific mortar compositions matching original lime-sand or Portland-lime mixes; incorrect mortar mix can damage historic brick. Chestnut Hill stone facades require specific pointing and cleaning protocols.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Philadelphia insulation integration with siding replacement is incentivized under PECO Smart House Call plus PGW conservation plus PHFA low-interest financing. Continuous exterior insulation (R-5 to R-10 rigid foam or mineral wool) outboard of sheathing plus fiber cement reduces thermal bridging. Rowhouse party walls naturally eliminate heat loss on shared elevations, concentrating envelope-upgrade payback on front and back elevations. Chestnut Hill stone facade insulation typically uses interior furring and batt rather than exterior retrofit. Blower-door testing verifies air-tightness on conservation-improvement-funded jobs.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Philadelphia pressure-wash prep before siding installation: heavy biological growth on north-facing rowhouse elevations requires cleaning before new installation. 2,000-3,000 PSI pressure wash with bleach-based detergent on framed elevations; gentler 1,000-1,500 PSI on aged brick to avoid mortar erosion. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (vast majority of Philly) trigger EPA RRP with HEPA containment. Hidden-rot probe behind existing siding during initial assessment; rowhouse party-wall concealed moisture is a common Philly failure hidden during previous installation.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Philadelphia siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Philly from mid-Atlantic regional office. CertainTeed is headquartered in Malvern PA (Philly suburb) with direct local support. LP SmartSide ships from regional distribution. Mastic (Ply Gem) handles vinyl. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple Philly and suburban locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products. Mid-Atlantic distribution hub serves Philly with 1-3 day lead times on most major brands. Rowhouse supply and specialty products from Philadelphia Salvage and Material Culture.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Philadelphia siding installer tiering: rowhouse-specialty crews with both L&I Contractor License AND HICPA registration run $12-$22 per square foot on rowhouse-specific work. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $14-$24 per square foot on fiber cement on suburban framed housing. Philadelphia Historical Commission landmark-restoration crews run $25-$48 per square foot on Society Hill, Old City, and Chestnut Hill projects. Philly labor premium over national average runs 1.3-1.6x. Both L&I Contractor License AND PA HICPA registration must be active and on contract.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Philadelphia siding upsells worth accepting on framed rowhouse work: drainage-plane weather-resistive barrier, continuous exterior insulation coordinated with PECO rebates, HardieColor Plus factory finish, lead-safe substrate preparation. On rowhouse brick: proper tuckpointing with lime-sand mortar matching original composition rather than modern Portland-only mixes that damage historic brick. Upsells to decline: "rowhouse-specialist" proprietary products without independent testing, vinyl on landmarked facades (prohibited), and contractors claiming both L&I and HICPA without verifying both separately.`,
    marketSizePara: `Philadelphia city has approximately 565,000 residential structures including 260,000+ rowhouse trinity and three-story twins plus 180,000 pitched-roof single-family plus 125,000 multi-family. Philadelphia metro (Bucks, Chester, Delaware, Montgomery, Philadelphia counties plus South Jersey) totals approximately 1.7 million residential. Brick dominates rowhouse at 80-85%, with fiber cement and wood on framed elevations. Philly L&I pulls approximately 10,000-18,000 siding permits annually city-wide. Philadelphia Historical Commission landmarked siding scope represents 3-6% of annual city total (higher than most metros).`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Philadelphia siding pricing peaks April through June and September through October during optimal install conditions between winter freeze and summer humidity extremes. November through March sub-freezing ambient compromises vinyl impact resistance and caulk activation; most Philly contractors stop vinyl work when below 32F. Fiber cement can install in cold weather with proper primer but labor premiums run 15-25% from December through February. Best pricing typically runs October-November (10-15% below peak). Philadelphia Historical Commission review on Society Hill, Old City, and Chestnut Hill often dictates scheduling more than weather.`,
  },
  "miami-fl": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Miami's dominant siding material is 3-coat stucco on CBS (concrete block stucco) construction across Coral Gables, Pinecrest, Coconut Grove, South Miami, and most single-family residential, which dominates at 85-90% of housing. Hardie fiber cement on higher-end renovations and Miami Beach Art Deco District work where approved by historic commission. Vinyl on older framed housing but restricted by Miami-Dade HVHZ wind-uplift requirements in many neighborhoods. Brick veneer on a minority of tract construction. Mediterranean Revival homes in Coral Gables use specific stucco texture matching Merrick-era originals.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Miami-Dade has designated historic districts and landmarks including Coral Gables (Merrick-era 1920s Mediterranean Revival), Miami Beach Art Deco District (world's largest concentration of Art Deco architecture), MiMo Biscayne Boulevard (Miami Modernism), Morningside, South Pointe, Pinecrest-Kenwood, Stiltsville, and Virginia Key Beach. Coral Gables historic preservation authority is among the strictest in the US, requiring material, color, and architectural profile matching to Merrick-era originals. Approved siding materials typically include period-appropriate stucco matching specific textures and colors, or specific profile wood on rare framed elevations.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `Miami-Dade Building Department permits residential siding replacement through the ePlan portal within 7-14 business days at $250 minimum. Broward County uses separate permits with similar timelines. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-6 weeks. Coral Gables, Miami Beach, Morningside historic review adds 6-14 weeks on contributing properties. Florida DBPR Certified Specialty Contractor (C-22) or Certified General Contractor license required for permit-pulling. Miami-Dade HVHZ compliance requires specific wind-uplift rated products. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Miami coastal zones (all of Miami Beach, Key Biscayne, Bal Harbour, Surfside, Sunny Isles, Fisher Island, and Atlantic-facing properties) experience severe salt-air corrosion. Stainless steel 316 fasteners are the durable Miami coastal spec (even 304 stainless can pit in severe salt exposure); galvanized steel pits and stains within 2-4 years. Marine-coated aluminum, bronze, or copper trim are coastal-durable. Hurricane wind-borne debris testing per Florida Building Code R609 and Miami-Dade HVHZ requirements drive product selection. Salt-air also degrades paint film; coastal-grade paints with specific chemistry extend service.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Miami paint-compatibility considerations: 6-10 year re-paint cycles in tropical humidity and UV, 15-year factory-finish fiber cement ColorPlus is meaningfully longer. Coastal-grade exterior paints (Benjamin Moore Aura exterior, Sherwin-Williams Duration, specific coastal formulations) outperform standard paints. Mildew-resistant additives are essential; dark colors fade within 6-8 years on south and west elevations. Coral Gables Mediterranean Revival restoration requires specific color matching to Merrick-era palette (searchable at Coral Gables Historic Preservation office). Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Miami insulation integration with siding replacement is less common on CBS (concrete block stucco) construction due to thermal-mass effect of block walls. Framed siding sections on gables, dormers, and second-story can integrate R-5 to R-8 rigid foam outboard of sheathing. FPL Home Energy Survey rebates apply to ENERGY STAR-qualifying envelope upgrades. Radiant barrier on wall assembly reduces solar gain on west-facing elevations. Hurricane wind-uplift requirements limit some insulation-integration options because exterior foam can complicate wind-mitigation detailing.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Miami pressure-wash prep before siding installation: heavy biological growth on north-facing elevations (mildew, algae) requires aggressive cleaning before new installation. 2,500-3,500 PSI pressure wash with bleach-based detergent (3-5% sodium hypochlorite solution) on CBS stucco is Miami standard. Hurricane-damage assessment before substrate preparation; post-hurricane crack propagation in stucco requires specific repair protocols. Salt-air-damaged metal fasteners and aluminum trim require replacement before new siding installation. Termite inspection of wood fascia on pre-hurricane-era homes is essential.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Miami siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Miami from Southeast regional office. CertainTeed operates from Shakopee MN and Florida plants. LP SmartSide ships from regional distribution. Regional stucco suppliers include Targa Supply, Florida Block, and Cemex. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple Miami-Dade locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products with same-day pickup. Miami-Dade HVHZ-approved product lists published at miamidade.gov/pa; every product used must appear on the current list.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Miami siding installer tiering: stucco-specialty crews dominate CBS residential recoat at $5-$10 per square foot on elastomeric or $9-$16 per square foot on 3-coat. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $11-$20 per square foot on fiber cement. Coral Gables and Miami Beach historic-restoration crews run $22-$48 per square foot on landmarked projects (specialty restoration with strict compliance review). Miami labor premium over national average runs 1.1-1.3x. Florida DBPR Certified Specialty Contractor (C-22) plus Miami-Dade County business tax receipt are mandatory baseline.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Miami siding upsells worth accepting: Miami-Dade HVHZ-approved products on exposed elevations, stainless 316 fasteners in coastal salt-air zones, elastomeric crack-bridging coating on stucco recoat (critical in hurricane-season moisture), coastal-grade paint formulations, and Coral Gables color-matching on Merrick-era restoration. Upsells to decline: non-HVHZ products on coastal-adjacent work (fails final inspection), AOB (Assignment of Benefits) signing on hurricane-claim work (14-day rescission under Florida Statute §627.7152), quickie elastomeric over structurally-cracked stucco, and "hurricane-proof" claims lacking current Notice of Acceptance.`,
    marketSizePara: `Miami-Dade County has approximately 620,000 single-family homes, with Broward County adding 560,000 and Palm Beach County 480,000. Stucco dominates CBS construction at roughly 85%, fiber cement at 8%, brick veneer at 3%, and other at 4%. Miami-Dade pulls approximately 20,000-32,000 siding permits annually. Post-hurricane recovery years add substantial volume (post-Irma 2017 saw 60,000+ annual permits metro-wide). Coral Gables and Miami Beach historic siding scope represents 4-7% of annual Miami-Dade total (higher than most metros).`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Miami siding pricing peaks December through April during snowbird-season demand and non-hurricane-season install. June through November hurricane season sees active install disrupted by tropical systems. Post-hurricane surge pricing can double normal rates for 6-12 months. Best pricing typically runs May and late November (10-15% below peak). January through March is the optimal combination of snowbird demand, non-hurricane-season, and comfortable install conditions. Coral Gables and Miami Beach Historic Commission review cycles dictate scheduling more than weather on landmarked projects.`,
  },
  "boston-ma": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Boston's dominant siding material is wood clapboard and cedar shake on colonial-era and triple-decker housing across Dorchester, Roxbury, Jamaica Plain, Somerville, Cambridge, and Brookline, which represents 50-60% of Boston-area residential. Brick masonry on Back Bay and Beacon Hill rowhouses (15-20% concentrated in landmark districts). Hardie fiber cement and wood composite on modern renovations in the South End, Jamaica Plain, and Brighton. Vinyl on value-tier installations in outer neighborhoods. Triple-decker clapboard requires specific three-story corner detailing absent in most US markets.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Boston has 7 locally designated historic districts and 50+ National Register-listed districts under Boston Landmarks Commission jurisdiction. Boston Landmarks districts include Back Bay, Beacon Hill, Fort Point, South End, Bay Village, Mission Hill Triangle, and St. Botolph. National Register districts include Chinatown-Leather District, Ladder District, North End, West End, Aberdeen, Audubon Circle, Savin Hill, Jamaica Plain, Roslindale Village, Dorchester Avenue, Charlestown Navy Yard, and Uphams Corner. Landmarked review applies to contributing structures; approved siding materials typically include wood clapboard matching original profile, brick restoration, or specific period materials.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `Boston Inspectional Services Department permits siding replacement through the Permit Center portal within 5-10 business days at $200 minimum. Suburban MA cities use separate permit processes. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-6 weeks. Boston Landmarks review adds 6-10 weeks on contributing properties. Massachusetts HIC registration plus Construction Supervisor License (CSL) both required for structural opening work. Scaffolding permits for triple-decker access add 2-3 weeks. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (vast majority of Boston triple-decker stock) trigger EPA RRP scope plus MA Deleading regulations.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Boston coastal zones (Winthrop, Nahant, Hull, Revere, East Boston waterfront) experience significant salt-air corrosion. Stainless steel 304 or 316 fasteners are the durable Boston coastal spec; galvanized steel pits within 5-7 years. Marine-coated aluminum or copper trim are coastal-durable. Massachusetts coastal zone designation adds regulatory overlay for properties within Massachusetts Coastal Zone Management jurisdiction. Boston winter road-salt spray across dense neighborhoods corrodes fasteners even in non-waterfront zones. Triple-decker roof-wall transitions and corner detailing see salt-spray accumulation.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Boston paint-compatibility considerations: 8-12 year re-paint cycles on wood clapboard due to nor'easter moisture and summer humidity, 15-year factory-finish fiber cement ColorPlus is meaningfully longer. Oil-based primers outperform acrylic on aged clapboard in Boston climate. Mildew-resistant additives essential. Back Bay Purple Glass requirement on specific historic addresses extends to specific trim color coordination. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (vast majority of Boston stock) trigger EPA RRP plus MA Deleading which is stricter than federal EPA RRP and requires MA-licensed Deleader.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Boston insulation integration with siding replacement is heavily incentivized under Mass Save sponsored by Eversource and National Grid. Continuous exterior insulation (R-5 to R-15 rigid foam or mineral wool) outboard of sheathing plus clapboard or fiber cement dramatically reduces thermal bridging. Massachusetts Stretch Code (780 CMR Appendix 115.AA) applies in Boston plus most inner-ring suburbs; replacement jobs may trigger blower-door testing. Triple-decker party-wall construction naturally eliminates heat loss on shared walls, concentrating envelope-upgrade payback on front, back, and end elevations.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Boston pressure-wash prep before siding installation: biological growth on north-facing triple-decker elevations requires cleaning before new installation. 2,000-3,000 PSI pressure wash with bleach-based detergent on framed elevations; gentler 1,000-1,500 PSI on aged brick in Back Bay. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP plus MA Deleading with specific containment protocols. Triple-decker hidden-rot probe behind existing clapboard during initial assessment; ice-dam water intrusion often creates concealed sheathing damage that must be repaired before new installation.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Boston siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Boston from New England regional office. CertainTeed operates from Shakopee MN and Roanoke VA plants. LP SmartSide ships from Midwest plants. Cedar for period restoration comes from New England Cedar Co. (ME), Maibec (QC), and other specialty mills. Local distributors include ABC Supply (Woburn, Stoughton), Beacon Building Products, and SRS Distribution. Massachusetts HIC registration plus CSL both required and publicly searchable at mass.gov. MA Deleader license mandatory for pre-1978 home work.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Boston siding installer tiering: small owner-operator crews with HIC registration run $10-$18 per square foot on standard suburban work. Triple-decker-specialty crews with both HIC and CSL run $14-$26 per square foot on three-story Dorchester and Somerville work. Boston Landmarks-restoration crews run $28-$55 per square foot on Back Bay, Beacon Hill, and South End landmarked projects. Boston labor premium over national average runs 1.4-1.7x due to high cost of living. Both HIC registration AND CSL must be active and on contract for structural work.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Boston siding upsells worth accepting: continuous exterior insulation (Mass Save rebates + R-15+ total assembly meets Stretch Code), stainless-steel fasteners on coastal-adjacent properties, wood clapboard factory-primed and back-primed (doubles paint service life), ice-dam protection coordination with wall-roof transitions, MA-compliant Deleading on pre-1978 homes. Upsells to decline: "New England-specific" proprietary products without independent testing, vinyl on landmarked facades (prohibited), field-priming-only (manufacturer warranty void), and contractors claiming HIC without separate verified CSL for structural work.`,
    marketSizePara: `Boston metro (Suffolk, Middlesex, Norfolk, Essex, Plymouth counties) has approximately 1.2 million residential structures including 180,000+ triple-deckers concentrated in Dorchester, Somerville, Cambridge, and South Boston. Wood clapboard and cedar shake dominate at roughly 55% combined, brick at 15% (concentrated in landmark districts), fiber cement at 15%, vinyl at 10%, and other at 5%. Boston ISD pulls approximately 8,000-15,000 siding permits annually city-wide; metro-wide runs 28,000-48,000. Boston Landmarks landmarked siding scope represents 4-7% of annual city total.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Boston siding pricing peaks May through early October during reliable install-weather window. November through April sub-freezing ambient compromises vinyl impact resistance and caulk activation; most MA contractors stop vinyl work when below 32F. Fiber cement and wood clapboard can install in cold weather with proper primer but labor premiums run 20-35% from December through February. Best pricing typically runs late September and May (10-18% below peak). Boston Landmarks review on Back Bay, Beacon Hill, and South End often dictates scheduling more than weather.`,
  },
  "san-diego-ca": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `San Diego's dominant siding material is 3-coat stucco on Spanish Colonial and Mediterranean homes across La Jolla, Rancho Santa Fe, Point Loma, Kensington, Mission Hills, and most single-family residential, which dominates at 60-70% of housing. Fiber cement (James Hardie HardiePlank) on mid-range renovations and modern-style homes. Wood siding on historic Mission Hills, South Park, and La Jolla craftsman homes. Vinyl is uncommon due to coastal aesthetic tradition and WUI fire-hazard restrictions in inland zones. Coastal SD homes within 1 mile of the beach require specialty marine-coated fasteners.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `San Diego has multiple designated historic districts and Mills Act properties under San Diego Historic Resources Board jurisdiction including Mission Hills, Burlingame, South Park, Uptown, La Jolla, Coronado Crown-Manor, Balboa Park, Old Town San Diego State Historic Park, Gaslamp Quarter, Marston Hills, Mission Beach, Pacific Beach, Point Loma, Sherman Heights, University Heights, and West Bankers Hill. Landmark review applies to contributing structures. Approved siding materials typically include period-appropriate stucco matching Spanish Colonial textures, original-matching wood clapboard on craftsman homes, or specific profile restoration on 1900s-1940s construction.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `San Diego Development Services Department permits siding replacement through the DSD portal within 5-10 business days at $195 minimum. County of San Diego unincorporated uses separate permits. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-6 weeks. San Diego Historic Resources Board review adds 6-10 weeks on Mills Act or landmarked properties. California CSLB license mandatory (C-35 plastering for stucco, C-6 cabinet/millwork for wood, C-61 for siding specialty, or B general). California Coastal Commission jurisdiction adds regulatory overlay for coastal-zone properties. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `San Diego coastal zones (La Jolla, Del Mar, Encinitas, Solana Beach, Cardiff, Ocean Beach, Pacific Beach, Coronado, Imperial Beach) experience severe salt-air corrosion. Stainless steel 316 fasteners are the durable SD coastal spec; galvanized steel pits within 2-4 years in Pacific salt environments. Marine-coated aluminum, bronze, or copper trim are coastal-durable. California Coastal Commission jurisdiction adds permit complexity. WUI fire-zone exposure in Rancho Bernardo, Rancho Peñasquitos, Scripps Ranch, and East County drives Class A fire-rated assembly requirements. Stucco in marine environments requires specific waterproofing.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `San Diego paint-compatibility considerations: 8-12 year re-paint cycles in coastal-marine climate, 15-year factory-finish fiber cement ColorPlus is meaningfully longer. Coastal-grade exterior paints (Benjamin Moore Aura exterior, Sherwin-Williams Duration coastal formulations, Dunn-Edwards marine) outperform standard paints. Mildew-resistant additives essential. Salt-air degrades paint film at roughly 1.5x the rate of inland climates; coastal re-paint cycles run 6-9 years. Historic Mission Hills and La Jolla restoration requires period-accurate color palettes. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `San Diego insulation integration with siding replacement is incentivized under SDG&E Home Energy Efficiency Rebate and San Diego Regional Climate Action Plan. Continuous exterior insulation (R-5 to R-8 rigid foam) outboard of sheathing reduces thermal bridging. Title 24 Part 6 (2022) requires specific wall assembly performance. California Coastal Commission may require specific insulation systems in coastal-zone properties. WUI fire-zone properties require Class A fire-rated assemblies. Spray foam cavity insulation coordinated with siding tear-off adds R-value at modest cost.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `San Diego pressure-wash prep before siding installation: coastal salt-spray accumulation and biological growth require cleaning before new installation. 2,000-3,000 PSI pressure wash with detergent on stucco; gentler 1,000-1,500 PSI on aged wood to avoid fiber damage. Salt-air-damaged fasteners and aluminum trim require replacement before new siding. WUI fire-zone properties require specific cleanup protocols to avoid ember-source residue. Mills Act historic properties require specific cleaning protocols to preserve aged patina and original detail. Termite inspection on pre-1980 homes is prudent.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `San Diego siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers SD from California regional office. CertainTeed operates from California plants. LP SmartSide ships from regional distribution. La Habra Stucco (La Habra CA) is dominant regional stucco manufacturer. Cedar and redwood for coastal craftsman restoration from Mendocino Redwood (CA) and Humboldt Redwood (CA). Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple SD locations), Beacon Building Products (Chula Vista, San Marcos), SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products with same-day pickup. Active CSLB plus SD city business tax certificate required.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `San Diego siding installer tiering: stucco-specialty crews (C-35 plastering license) run $9-$16 per square foot on 3-coat stucco on standard Spanish Colonial work. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $12-$22 per square foot on fiber cement. Mills Act historic-restoration crews run $22-$42 per square foot on Mission Hills, Burlingame, and La Jolla landmarked projects. WUI Class A fire-rated installer pool is more limited. SD labor premium over national average runs 1.3-1.6x due to high cost of living. Active CSLB license plus SD city or county business tax certificate required.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `San Diego siding upsells worth accepting: stainless 316 fasteners on coastal-adjacent properties (prevents 2-4 year fastener failure), Class A fire-rated assembly in WUI zones (mandatory for FAIR Plan eligibility), coastal-grade paint formulations, drainage-plane weather-resistive barrier (critical in marine-adjacent zones), and HardieColor Plus factory finish on fiber cement. Upsells to decline: non-Class-A products in WUI zones (compliance failure), unnecessary decorative additions beyond existing facade profile, "coastal-specific" proprietary products lacking California Coastal Commission documentation, and uncoated aluminum in marine zones.`,
    marketSizePara: `San Diego County has approximately 780,000 single-family homes. Stucco dominates at roughly 62%, fiber cement at 15%, wood siding at 8% (concentrated in craftsman and Mills Act historic neighborhoods), vinyl at 5%, brick veneer at 3%, and other at 7%. SD DSD plus County pulls approximately 14,000-25,000 siding permits annually across all replacement scope. Historic Resources Board landmarked siding scope represents 3-5% of annual total. Stucco recoat projects are often permitted as maintenance rather than replacement. Mills Act property-tax reductions drive incentive for landmark-compliant restoration.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `San Diego siding pricing is relatively stable year-round due to mild Mediterranean climate, with modest peak September-November and spring-storm-season claim surges. Winter (December-February) atmospheric-river rainfall disrupts stucco cure briefly. Summer WUI fire-season access restrictions affect hillside scheduling from late June through October during Red Flag Warning days. Best pricing typically runs January-March and June (5-12% below peak). California Coastal Commission permit cycles dictate timing on coastal-zone properties more than weather.`,
  },
  "tampa-fl": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Tampa's dominant siding material is 3-coat stucco on CBS (concrete block stucco) construction across Hillsborough and Pinellas counties, which dominates at 75-85% of Tampa residential. Hardie fiber cement on higher-end renovations in Hyde Park, South Tampa, Davis Islands, and Westshore. Vinyl on older framed cottages in Seminole Heights and Tampa Heights but restricted by Florida Product Approval wind-borne debris requirements in coastal-adjacent zones. Tampa Bay-facing properties require specific salt-resistant fasteners. Brick veneer on a minority of tract construction in Brandon and New Tampa.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Tampa has 6 locally designated historic districts and multiple National Register-listed districts under Historic Preservation Commission jurisdiction including Hyde Park, Seminole Heights, Tampa Heights, Ybor City, V.M. Ybor Historic District, Tampa Bay Hotel, Old Hyde Park Preservation District, West Tampa, and Dundee Historic District. Landmark review applies to contributing structures. Approved siding materials typically include period-appropriate stucco matching Florida vernacular textures, wood clapboard on framed bungalow-era homes, or specific profile restoration on 1900s-1940s construction. Ybor City brick requires specific repointing protocols.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `Tampa-Hillsborough County Building Department permits siding replacement through the Electronic Plans Review (ePRS) portal within 7-14 business days at $175 minimum plus FPA documentation verification for coastal-adjacent installations. Pinellas County uses separate permits. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-6 weeks. Tampa Historic Preservation review adds 6-10 weeks on contributing properties. Florida DBPR Certified Specialty Contractor (C-22) or Certified General Contractor license required. Wind-borne debris region installations require documented FPA approval. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Tampa coastal zones (South Tampa, Davis Islands, Clearwater Beach, Dunedin, St. Pete Beach, Treasure Island, Indian Rocks Beach) experience significant salt-air corrosion. Stainless steel 316 fasteners are the durable Tampa coastal spec; galvanized steel pits within 3-5 years in Gulf salt environments. Marine-coated aluminum, bronze, or copper trim are coastal-durable. Hurricane wind-borne debris testing per Florida Building Code R609 drives product selection. Florida Product Approval (FPA) wind-borne debris region installations (within 1 mile of coast) require specific fastener spacing and product ratings.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Tampa paint-compatibility considerations: 6-10 year re-paint cycles in tropical Gulf Coast humidity and UV, 15-year factory-finish fiber cement ColorPlus is meaningfully longer. Coastal-grade exterior paints (Benjamin Moore Aura exterior, Sherwin-Williams Duration, specific coastal formulations) outperform standard paints. Mildew-resistant additives are essential in 80%+ humidity. Dark colors fade within 6-8 years on south and west elevations. Historic Hyde Park and Seminole Heights restoration requires period-accurate color palettes. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Tampa insulation integration with siding replacement is less common on CBS construction due to thermal-mass effect of block walls. Framed sections on gables, dormers, and second-story can integrate R-5 to R-8 rigid foam. TECO Peoples Gas plus Duke Energy Florida rebates apply to ENERGY STAR-qualifying envelope upgrades. Radiant barrier on wall assembly reduces solar gain on west-facing elevations. Florida Product Approval wind-uplift requirements limit some insulation-integration options on coastal-adjacent installations because exterior foam can complicate wind-mitigation detailing.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Tampa pressure-wash prep before siding installation: heavy biological growth (mildew, algae) on north-facing elevations requires aggressive cleaning before new installation. 2,500-3,500 PSI pressure wash with bleach-based detergent (3-5% sodium hypochlorite) on CBS stucco is Tampa standard. Hurricane-damage assessment before substrate preparation; post-hurricane crack propagation in stucco requires specific repair protocols. Salt-air-damaged metal components require replacement before new installation. Termite inspection of wood fascia on pre-hurricane-era homes is essential.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Tampa siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Tampa Bay from Florida regional office. CertainTeed operates from Shakopee MN and Florida plants. LP SmartSide ships from regional distribution. Regional stucco suppliers include Targa Supply, Florida Block, and Cemex. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple Hillsborough and Pinellas locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products with same-day pickup. Florida DBPR licensing and Hillsborough or Pinellas County business tax receipt publicly verifiable.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Tampa siding installer tiering: stucco-specialty crews dominate CBS residential recoat at $5-$10 per square foot on elastomeric or $8-$15 per square foot on 3-coat. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $10-$18 per square foot on fiber cement. Tampa Historic Preservation landmark-restoration crews run $22-$45 per square foot on Hyde Park, Seminole Heights, and Ybor City projects. Tampa labor premium over national average runs 1.0-1.2x due to favorable cost of living. Florida DBPR C-22 or CGC license plus county business tax receipt are mandatory baseline for permit-pulling.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Tampa siding upsells worth accepting: FPA-approved products on coastal-adjacent work, stainless 316 fasteners in coastal salt-air zones, elastomeric crack-bridging coating on stucco recoat, coastal-grade paint formulations on Gulf-facing elevations, and hurricane wind-mitigation detailing on framed sections. Upsells to decline: non-FPA products on coastal-adjacent work (fails final inspection), AOB signing on hurricane-claim work (14-day rescission under Florida Statute §627.7152), quickie elastomeric over structurally-cracked stucco, and "hurricane-proof" claims lacking current FPA or Notice of Acceptance.`,
    marketSizePara: `Tampa Bay metro (Hillsborough, Pinellas, Pasco, Hernando, Manatee counties) has approximately 1.4 million single-family homes. Stucco dominates CBS construction at roughly 78%, fiber cement at 10%, vinyl at 6%, brick veneer at 3%, and other at 3%. Tampa-Hillsborough plus Pinellas pulls approximately 14,000-26,000 siding permits annually. Post-hurricane recovery years add substantial volume (post-Irma 2017 saw 35,000+ annual permits metro-wide). Tampa Historic Preservation landmarked siding scope represents 3-5% of annual total. Stucco recoat projects often permitted as maintenance.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Tampa siding pricing peaks December through April during snowbird-season demand and non-hurricane-season install. June through November hurricane season sees active install disrupted by tropical systems. Post-hurricane surge pricing can double normal rates for 6-12 months. Best pricing typically runs May and late November (10-15% below peak). January through March is the optimal combination of snowbird demand, non-hurricane-season, and comfortable install conditions. Tampa Historic Preservation review cycles on Hyde Park and Ybor City often dictate scheduling more than weather on landmarked projects.`,
  },
  "detroit-mi": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Detroit's dominant siding material is brick masonry on 1910s-1940s brick bungalows and Arts-and-Crafts homes across Detroit proper and suburban Oakland, Macomb, and Wayne counties, which dominates at 50-60% of residential. Wood clapboard on framed bungalows and Tudor homes. Vinyl on value-tier replacements in outer neighborhoods. Hardie fiber cement and wood composite on higher-end renovations in Boston-Edison, Indian Village, Woodbridge, Palmer Park, and Corktown. Detroit brick requires tuckpointing rather than replacement; framed siding faces the full severe-climate challenge of Great Lakes freeze-thaw.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Detroit has 20+ designated historic districts under Detroit Historic Designation Advisory Board jurisdiction including Boston-Edison, Indian Village, Woodbridge, Palmer Park, Corktown, East Ferry Avenue, Atkinson Avenue, Willis-Selden, West Canfield, Brush Park, Virginia Park, Prentis Avenue, Arden Park-East Boston, Hubbard Farms, Warren Avenue West, Parkview, New Center Commercial, Cass-Davenport, Piquette Avenue, and Thirteen-Hundred Block East Lafayette. Landmarked review applies to contributing structures. Approved siding materials include period-appropriate wood clapboard, brick restoration, or specific fiber cement matching 1900s-1940s patterns.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `City of Detroit Buildings, Safety Engineering, and Environmental Department permits siding replacement within 5-10 business days at $100 minimum. Wayne, Oakland, Macomb counties use separate permit processes. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-5 weeks. Detroit Historic Designation Advisory Board review adds 4-8 weeks on contributing structures. Michigan LARA Residential Builder license required for permit-pulling. Michigan Consumer Protection Act (MCL §339) requires three-day right-of-rescission on any in-home sale; contracts without that notice are unenforceable. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Detroit has no coastal saltwater exposure but Lake St. Clair and Lake Erie shoreline properties experience freeze-thaw moisture cycling similar to other Great Lakes markets. Detroit winter road-salt spray across urban neighborhoods corrodes fasteners and aluminum trim within 5-7 years on uncoated galvanized steel. Stainless steel 304 fasteners outperform galvanized. Lake-effect snow-load at roof-wall transitions drives structural-reinforcement on some tear-off renovations. Freeze-thaw cycling on framed-siding stud cavities can drive moisture accumulation if not properly detailed.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Detroit paint-compatibility considerations: 8-12 year re-paint cycles on wood clapboard due to Great Lakes freeze-thaw and summer humidity, 15-year factory-finish fiber cement ColorPlus is meaningfully longer. Oil-based primers outperform acrylic on aged wood substrates in Detroit climate. Mildew-resistant additives essential. Detroit freeze-thaw is particularly hard on paint film adhesion; failed paint on north-facing elevations typically requires full strip-and-refinish rather than touch-up. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (vast majority of Detroit housing stock) trigger EPA RRP.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Detroit insulation integration with siding replacement is incentivized under DTE Energy Home Energy Consultation plus Consumers Energy efficiency rebates. Continuous exterior insulation (R-8 to R-15 rigid foam or mineral wool) outboard of sheathing plus fiber cement dramatically reduces thermal bridging in cold Great Lakes climate. Michigan Residential Code with 2015 IECC amendments requires air-leakage verification on conservation-improvement-funded jobs. R-20+ total wall assembly meets Detroit Stretch-Code-adjacent performance. Blower-door testing verifies air-tightness.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Detroit pressure-wash prep before siding installation: freeze-thaw-damaged substrates require moisture testing and repair before new installation. 2,000-3,000 PSI pressure wash with detergent removes biological growth and loose paint. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (nearly all Detroit housing) trigger EPA RRP with HEPA containment. High-pressure water washing of lead-painted substrates is prohibited except with specific containment protocols. Landmark-district historic properties require specific cleaning protocols to preserve original molding and detail.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Detroit siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Detroit from Midwest regional office. CertainTeed operates from Avery OH and Shakopee MN plants. LP SmartSide ships from Midwest plants with 2-4 day lead times. Mastic (Ply Gem) handles vinyl. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple Detroit-area locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products. Michigan LARA Residential Builder license mandatory and publicly searchable at michigan.gov/lara. Detroit Better Business Bureau publishes contractor complaint history at bbb.org/detroit.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Detroit siding installer tiering: small owner-operator vinyl-specialty crews dominate value-tier tract replacement at $7-$12 per square foot installed. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $10-$18 per square foot on fiber cement. Detroit Historic Designation Advisory Board landmark-restoration crews run $18-$32 per square foot on Boston-Edison, Indian Village, and Corktown projects. Detroit labor premium over national average runs 0.9-1.1x due to favorable cost of living. Michigan LARA Residential Builder license plus workers' compensation and insurance certificates are verifiable baseline.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Detroit siding upsells worth accepting: continuous exterior insulation (DTE rebate eligibility), .046"+ gauge vinyl (avoids cold-weather impact failure), fiber cement factory-finished ColorPlus (15-year fade warranty), lead-safe substrate preparation on pre-1978 homes, and drainage-plane weather-resistive barrier. Upsells to decline: "Detroit-tough" proprietary vinyl without documented cold-weather impact testing, unnecessary decorative additions beyond existing facade profile, builder-grade .040" thin-gauge vinyl that cracks in sub-zero ambient, and in-home sales pitches lacking the Michigan MCL §339.2411 three-day rescission notice.`,
    marketSizePara: `Detroit metro (Wayne, Oakland, Macomb, Washtenaw, St. Clair, Monroe, Livingston, Lapeer counties) has approximately 1.6 million residential structures. Brick veneer and brick masonry dominate at roughly 48%, vinyl at 22%, wood at 12%, fiber cement at 10%, and other at 8%. City of Detroit BSEED pulls approximately 5,000-10,000 siding permits annually city-wide; metro-wide runs 35,000-55,000. Post-2023 derecho recovery added significant volume across Oakland and Macomb counties. Detroit Historic Designation Advisory Board landmarked siding scope represents 2-4% of annual city total.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Detroit siding pricing peaks April through October during the reliable install-weather window between winter freeze and summer humidity extremes. November through March sub-freezing ambient compromises vinyl impact resistance and caulk activation; most Detroit contractors stop vinyl work when below 32F. Fiber cement can install in cold weather with proper primer but labor premiums run 20-35% from December through February. Best pricing typically runs late September and October (10-18% below peak). Detroit Historic Designation Advisory Board review often dictates scheduling more than weather.`,
  },
  "minneapolis-mn": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Minneapolis's dominant siding material is wood lap siding and vinyl on 1920s-1950s bungalows and four-squares across Uptown, Linden Hills, Lowry Hill, Lake Calhoun, and Nokomis, which represents 45-55% of Minneapolis residential. Hardie fiber cement on mid-range and higher-end renovations in Kenwood, Macalester-Groveland, and North Oaks. Brick appears on commercial-style residential and landmarked homes. Thicker vinyl (.046" or heavier) or fiber cement are the practical Minneapolis specs to handle sustained -20F winter temperatures. Thin-gauge vinyl fails on impact at severe cold.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Minneapolis has 10+ locally designated historic districts and multiple National Register-listed districts under Minneapolis Heritage Preservation Commission jurisdiction including Milwaukee Avenue, Nicollet Island, Healy Block, Fourth Avenue Historic District, Stevens Square, Fulton Neighborhood, Washburn-Fair Oaks Mansion, Saint Anthony Falls, Warehouse Historic District, and Grain Belt Brewery Complex. Landmark review applies to contributing structures. Approved siding materials typically include period-appropriate wood clapboard, brick restoration, or specific fiber cement matching 1890s-1930s bungalow and four-square patterns.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `Minneapolis Development Services permits siding replacement through the Minneapolis ePlans portal within 5-10 business days at $175 minimum. St. Paul uses separate permits. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-5 weeks. Heritage Preservation Commission review adds 4-8 weeks on contributing structures. Minnesota LARA Residential Building Contractor license required for jobs over $15,000; Residential Remodeler license for smaller jobs. Minneapolis also requires city contractor registration. Minnesota Energy Code mandates air-leakage verification on conservation-improvement-funded jobs. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes trigger EPA RRP.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Minneapolis has no coastal saltwater exposure; corrosion concerns center on Great Lakes influenced freeze-thaw moisture cycling and heavy winter road-salt spray across the metro. Minneapolis winter salt-spray corrodes fasteners and aluminum trim within 5-7 years on uncoated galvanized steel. Stainless steel 304 fasteners outperform galvanized in the 100+ annual freeze-thaw cycles. Dimensional stability of the siding material matters more here than in any other metro: materials expand and contract dramatically across the seasonal temperature range, stressing seams and fasteners over 20-30 year service.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Minneapolis paint-compatibility considerations: 7-10 year re-paint cycles on wood clapboard due to extreme freeze-thaw cycling, 15-year factory-finish fiber cement ColorPlus is meaningfully longer. Oil-based primers outperform acrylic on aged wood substrates in Twin Cities climate. Minneapolis freeze-thaw is among the most hostile paint environments in the country; failed paint on north-facing elevations typically requires full strip-and-refinish. Mildew-resistant additives essential in summer humidity extremes. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (most Twin Cities housing) trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Minneapolis insulation integration with siding replacement is heavily incentivized under Xcel Energy Minnesota plus CenterPoint Energy plus Home Energy Squad program. Continuous exterior insulation (R-10 to R-20 rigid foam or mineral wool) outboard of sheathing plus fiber cement dramatically reduces thermal bridging in very-cold continental Minneapolis climate. Minnesota Energy Code mandates air-leakage verification on whole-home weatherization. R-25+ total wall assembly performance meets Minnesota Stretch Code. Blower-door testing verifies air-tightness on conservation-improvement-funded jobs.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Minneapolis pressure-wash prep before siding installation: extreme freeze-thaw-damaged substrates require moisture testing using moisture meter and repair before new installation. 2,000-3,000 PSI pressure wash with detergent. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (vast majority of Twin Cities housing) trigger EPA RRP with HEPA containment. Heritage Preservation Commission historic properties require specific cleaning protocols to preserve original detail. Hidden-rot probe behind existing siding during assessment; ice-dam water intrusion creates concealed sheathing damage that must be repaired.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Minneapolis siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Twin Cities from Midwest regional office. CertainTeed operates from Shakopee MN plant (Twin Cities-adjacent) with same-day delivery. LP SmartSide manufactures in Hayward WI providing 1-2 day lead times. Mastic (Ply Gem) handles vinyl. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple Twin Cities locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products with same-day pickup. Minnesota LARA licensing and Minneapolis city contractor registration publicly verifiable. CertainTeed's Shakopee plant provides favorable lead times.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Minneapolis siding installer tiering: small owner-operator vinyl-specialty crews run $8-$14 per square foot on value-tier work. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $11-$19 per square foot on fiber cement. Heritage Preservation Commission landmark-restoration crews run $20-$38 per square foot on Milwaukee Avenue, Fourth Avenue, and Nicollet Island projects. Minneapolis labor premium over national average runs 1.1-1.3x. Minnesota LARA Residential Building Contractor license plus Minneapolis city contractor registration are mandatory baseline for permit-pulling.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Minneapolis siding upsells worth accepting: .046"+ gauge vinyl or fiber cement (avoids cold-weather impact failure at -20F), continuous exterior insulation (Xcel and CenterPoint rebate eligibility, R-15+ for Stretch Code), fiber cement factory-finished ColorPlus (15-year fade warranty), lead-safe substrate preparation on pre-1978 homes, and drainage-plane weather-resistive barrier. Upsells to decline: builder-grade .040" thin-gauge vinyl that cracks in sub-zero ambient, "Twin Cities-tough" proprietary products without documented cold-weather testing, unnecessary decorative additions beyond existing facade profile.`,
    marketSizePara: `Minneapolis-St. Paul metro (Hennepin, Ramsey, Dakota, Anoka, Washington, Carver, Scott counties) has approximately 1.3 million single-family homes. Wood lap siding dominates at roughly 35%, vinyl at 28%, fiber cement at 15%, brick at 12%, and other at 10%. Minneapolis Development Services plus St. Paul pull approximately 6,000-12,000 siding permits annually; metro-wide runs 28,000-45,000. Post-hail-event recovery years add substantial volume. Heritage Preservation Commission landmarked siding scope represents 2-3% of annual city total.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Minneapolis siding pricing peaks May through September during the reliable install-weather window. October through April sub-freezing ambient compromises vinyl impact resistance and caulk activation; most Minnesota contractors stop vinyl work from mid-October through late April and reschedule to spring. This compresses peak-season demand into 5 months, making summer bookings very competitive (12-20 week lead times after hail events). Fiber cement can install in cold weather with proper primer but labor premiums run 25-40% from November through March. Best pricing typically runs late September and May.`,
  },
  "charlotte-nc": {
    dominantMaterialPara: `Charlotte's dominant siding material is Hardie fiber cement on mid-range renovations across SouthPark, Ballantyne, Myers Park, and NoDa, which represents 25-35% of Charlotte residential. Brick veneer on newer tract construction in SouthPark, Ballantyne, and Providence Plantation. Wood lap siding on Dilworth and Plaza Midwood 1920s-1940s bungalows. Vinyl on value-tier replacements but HOA restrictions in SouthPark and Ballantyne typically require fiber cement or brick. Stucco on a minority of Mediterranean-style homes. Stone veneer on higher-end custom builds.`,
    historicDistrictPara: `Charlotte-Mecklenburg has designated historic districts under Historic District Commission jurisdiction including Dilworth, Wesley Heights, Fourth Ward, Plaza Midwood, Wilmore, Hermitage Court, Chantilly, Oaklawn Park, Biddleville-Seversville, Greenville, McCrorey Heights, and North Charlotte. National Register-listed districts add more coverage. Landmark review applies to contributing structures. Approved siding materials typically include period-appropriate wood clapboard, brick restoration, or specific fiber cement matching 1900s-1940s Piedmont Arts-and-Crafts and bungalow patterns. Cedar shingle on some original craftsman homes.`,
    permitsAndPrepPara: `Charlotte-Mecklenburg Planning Services permits siding replacement through the Accela portal within 5-10 business days at $150 minimum. Cabarrus, Gaston, Iredell, Union counties use separate permit processes. Scope changes trigger plan review at 2-5 weeks. Historic District Commission review adds 4-8 weeks on contributing structures. North Carolina Licensing Board for General Contractors requires state GC license for jobs over $30,000; Mecklenburg County contractor registration for smaller jobs. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (Dilworth and Plaza Midwood bungalows) trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    coastalCorrosionPara: `Charlotte has no coastal saltwater exposure; corrosion concerns center on Piedmont humidity-driven metal degradation and North Carolina red-clay soil movement that stresses framing over 15-20 year cycles. Galvanized steel fasteners perform adequately in Charlotte's inland climate for 15-25 year service. Stainless-steel fasteners provide longer service in hail-corridor Charlotte. Humidity-driven biological growth on north-facing elevations is aggressive; zinc or copper trim reduces biological growth. Termite exposure is severe; wood siding at grade-level elevations requires pressure-treated framing or fiber cement substitution.`,
    paintCompatibilityPara: `Charlotte paint-compatibility considerations: 8-12 year re-paint cycles on wood clapboard due to Piedmont humidity, 15-year factory-finish fiber cement ColorPlus is meaningfully longer. Mildew-resistant paint additives are essential; Benjamin Moore MoorGlo, Sherwin-Williams Duration with mildew resistance, Behr Premium Plus Ultra are Charlotte-proven. Oil-based primers outperform acrylic on aged wood. Pollen-season (February-March) coats active paint work and requires timing coordination. Lead-painted substrates on pre-1978 homes (Dilworth and Plaza Midwood bungalows) trigger EPA RRP scope.`,
    insulationIntegrationPara: `Charlotte insulation integration with siding replacement is common under Duke Energy Smart $aver Residential program. Continuous exterior insulation (R-5 to R-8 rigid foam) outboard of sheathing plus fiber cement reduces thermal bridging in humid-subtropical Piedmont climate. Spray foam on wood-framed siding substrates provides moisture resistance plus thermal improvement. Humidity management behind siding is critical Piedmont assembly-design factor; drainage-plane weather-resistive barrier with proper flashing prevents moisture accumulation. North Carolina Residential Code amendments post-Florence require enhanced wind-uplift on coastal-adjacent but increasingly common inland.`,
    pressureWashBeforePara: `Charlotte pressure-wash prep before siding installation: heavy biological growth on north-facing elevations requires aggressive cleaning before new installation. 2,500-3,500 PSI pressure wash with bleach-based detergent (3-5% sodium hypochlorite) is Charlotte standard. Termite inspection of wood fascia and sheathing before installation is essential; termite-damaged structural wood must be replaced before new siding installation. Pollen-season (February-March) site cleaning is Piedmont-specific before any exterior paint or siding work. Historic District Commission properties require specific cleaning protocols.`,
    manufacturerRepLandscapePara: `Charlotte siding manufacturer reps: James Hardie Territory Manager covers Charlotte from Southeast regional office (Hardie has strong SE presence). CertainTeed operates from Roanoke VA and Shakopee MN plants with Charlotte rep coverage. LP SmartSide ships from regional distribution. Mastic (Ply Gem) handles vinyl. Local distributors include ABC Supply (multiple Mecklenburg locations), Beacon Building Products, SRS Distribution, and Allied Building Products with same-day pickup. North Carolina Licensing Board for General Contractors publicly verifiable at nclbgc.org. Charlotte is a regional distribution hub with favorable lead times.`,
    localInstallerTieringPara: `Charlotte siding installer tiering: small owner-operator crews run $8-$14 per square foot on value-tier vinyl and entry-tier fiber cement. Mid-tier crews with HardieZone Preferred certification run $11-$19 per square foot on fiber cement. Historic District Commission landmark-restoration crews run $18-$34 per square foot on Dilworth, Plaza Midwood, and Myers Park projects. Charlotte labor premium over national average runs 1.0-1.2x. North Carolina Licensing Board for General Contractors license (required over $30,000) plus Mecklenburg County registration are verifiable baseline.`,
    commonUpsellPara: `Charlotte siding upsells worth accepting: drainage-plane weather-resistive barrier (critical in Piedmont humidity), pressure-treated framing at grade level (termite resistance), HardieColor Plus factory finish (15-year fade warranty), mildew-resistant paint additives, and zinc or copper trim on humidity-exposed elevations. Upsells to decline: "Piedmont-specific" proprietary products without documented biological-growth testing, unnecessary decorative additions beyond existing facade profile, cedar shingle in Charlotte humidity (degrades faster than most markets), and "tornado-proof" vinyl lacking documented testing.`,
    marketSizePara: `Charlotte metro (Mecklenburg, Cabarrus, Gaston, Iredell, Union, York SC, Lancaster SC counties) has approximately 950,000 single-family homes. Brick veneer dominates at roughly 50%, fiber cement at 22%, vinyl at 15%, wood at 5%, and other at 8%. Charlotte-Mecklenburg Planning plus suburban counties pull approximately 12,000-22,000 siding permits annually across all replacement scope. Post-hail-event recovery years add significant volume (2018 and 2023 hail drove 30,000+ annual permits). Historic District Commission landmarked siding scope represents 2-4% of annual county total.`,
    seasonalPricingPara: `Charlotte siding pricing peaks March through June during optimal install conditions between pollen season and summer humidity extremes, plus spring-storm claim surge. Pollen season (February-March) coats active work sites. July-August humidity and thunderstorm frequency disrupt install windows. October through December sees softer pricing (10-18% below peak) and faster scheduling. Best overall combination of pricing and install conditions runs October-November and April. Historic District Commission review on Dilworth and Plaza Midwood often dictates scheduling more than weather.`,
  },
};

