    warmEdgeDetailPara: `NYC warm-edge detailing on siding-to-window interface is critical in freeze-thaw coastal climate: continuous flashing with minimum 4-inch overlap at head, 6-inch at jamb, and 2-inch at sill is baseline. Back-dam and sill pan installation under window rough sill prevents moisture intrusion into wall cavity. Pre-war brownstone windows with original weight-and-pulley mechanisms require specialty detailing on siding integration where modern replacement windows retrofit into original masonry openings. NYC building-access restrictions on multi-family properties often force interior-side siding-to-window coordination during replacement scope.`,
    coldClimateDetailPara: `NYC cold-climate assembly details: continuous air barrier behind siding prevents wind-driven cold-air infiltration in pre-war stud cavities; building wrap (Tyvek, ZIP System) plus proper tape at all seams is the baseline NYC spec. Rain-screen drainage gap (3/8" minimum) between weather-resistive barrier and siding allows drying of wall assembly after nor'easter-driven moisture events. Vapor-open mineral wool outboard of sheathing performs well; closed-cell foam outboard can trap moisture in NYC climate. Termite barrier is less critical than in Southern metros.`,
    scaffoldAccessPara: `NYC scaffolding and access add significant cost to siding projects: pipe scaffold for three-story twin housing runs $4,000-$12,000 depending on duration and street exposure. Suspended scaffolding on rowhouse and apartment buildings requires DOB Scaffold Unit permits at $2,500-$12,000. Narrow alleys in Queens and Brooklyn limit scaffold staging; some properties require split-access scheduling over multiple weeks. Manhattan townhouse service-elevator scheduling and lobby protection plans add 2-4 weeks before work starts. Co-op board approval timelines add additional 4-8 weeks on multi-family buildings.`,
