    warmEdgeDetailPara: `Denver warm-edge detailing on siding-to-window interface: continuous flashing with minimum 6-inch overlap at head, 8-inch at jamb, 3-inch at sill (larger than standard due to high-altitude freeze-thaw and wind-driven rain). Back-dam and sill pan under window rough sill. Denver Green Code (voluntary but increasingly referenced) requires continuous air-barrier testing on retrofit energy-credit scope. Hail impact assessment at window-siding interface post-storm; hail damage to flashing integrity without visible exterior damage is common on Front Range replacements.`,
    coldClimateDetailPara: `Denver cold-climate assembly details: continuous air barrier behind siding prevents wind-driven cold-air infiltration at 5,280 feet altitude; chinook wind events drive 60-80 mph gusts stressing air barrier integrity. Rain-screen drainage gap between weather-resistive barrier and siding allows drying. Vapor-open mineral wool outboard of sheathing performs well; closed-cell foam outboard can trap moisture during summer humidity. 35-year silicone sealants at all penetrations outperform acrylic-latex in Denver freeze-thaw. High-altitude UV-stabilized formulations on exterior-exposed components.`,
    scaffoldAccessPara: `Denver scaffolding and access: pipe scaffold for two-story residential work runs $2,200-$6,500 depending on duration. Hillside and canyon-adjacent properties in Cherry Hills Village and Evergreen require specialty rental. Denver Landmark Preservation Commission jurisdictions (Capitol Hill, Country Club, Baker) require specific scaffolding protocols on landmarked facades. Post-hail recovery projects (2017, 2023) face regional scaffold scarcity with rental rates running 1.3-1.8x normal for 4-8 months. Denver DOTI permits for street-use scaffolding run $35-$75 per day plus tree-protection fees.`,
